# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: controversies-of-nestlé
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] A boycott was launched in the United States on July 4, 1977, against the Western multinational food and drink processing corporation Nestlé.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The boycott expanded into Europe in the early 1980s and was prompted by concerns about Nestlé's high-profile marketing of infant formulas as substitutes for breast milk, particularly in underdeveloped countries.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The boycott has been cancelled and renewed because of the business practices of Nestlé and other substitute manufacturers monitored by the International Baby Food Action Network (IBFAN).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Organizers of the boycott as well as public health researchers and experts consider breast milk to be the best nutrition source for infants.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The World Health Organization (WHO) recommends infants to be exclusively breastfed for the first six months of their lives, and nutritional gaps must be filled if breastfeeding is not possible.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The Nestlé boycott can be seen as special in a sense that it linked human rights regulations and humanitarian activism with corporate responsibility and market capitalism.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] One analysis argued consumers were basically acting as global citizens by aiding people in need outside their close communities, in this case mothers in developing countries, "using the marketplace not as a way of generating revenue, but rather as a space for protest".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In 2007, groups including the International Baby Food Action Network and Save the Children issued reports that the promotion of infant formula over breastfeeding led to health problems and deaths among infants in less economically developed countries.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Advocacy groups and charities have accused Nestlé of unethical methods of promoting infant formula over breast milk to poor mothers in developing countries.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] For example, IBFAN claims that Nestlé distributes free formula samples to hospitals and maternity wards; after leaving the hospital, the formula is no longer free, but because the supplementation has interfered with lactation, the family must continue to buy the formula.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] IBFAN also alleges that Nestlé uses "humanitarian aid" to create markets, does not label its products in a language appropriate to the countries where they are sold, and offers gifts and sponsorship to influence health workers to promote its products.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The company not only made use of mass media promotion (e.g. billboards and posters) and sample distributions, they also had sales people dressed as so-called "milk nurses" to visit mothers in hospital and at their home to praise formula and its benefits.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Nestlé justified its actions by rejecting the responsibility for e.g. the lack of clean water in many developing countries and further argued with freedom of consumer choice, which in the company's opinion allows for formula products to be sold in developing markets.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Nestlé's marketing strategy was first written about in *New Internationalist* magazine in 1973 and in a booklet called *The Baby Killer*, published by the British NGO War On Want in 1974.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The report helped raise concern over marketing practices in developing countries and served as the starting point of the so-called Baby Killer campaign.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Nestlé started a legal suit in Switzerland when the booklet was published in German language entitled "Nestlé kills Babies".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] After a two-year trial, the court found in favour of Nestlé because they could not be held responsible for the infant deaths 'in terms of criminal law'.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Because the defendants were only fined 300 Swiss Francs (just over US$400, adjusted for inflation), and Judge Jürg Sollberger commented that Nestlé "must modify its publicity methods fundamentally", *TIME* magazine declared this a "moral victory" for the defendants.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] This led to similar court challenges brought against other milk companies in the U.S. spearheaded by the Roman Catholic order Sisters of the Precious Blood in conjunction with the Interfaith Center on Corporate Responsibility.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In May 1978, the US Senate held a public hearing into the promotion of breast milk substitutes in developing countries and joined calls for a Marketing Code.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In 1979, WHO and UNICEF hosted an international meeting that called for the development of an international code of marketing, as well as action on other fronts to improve infant and early child feeding practices.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The International Baby Food Action Network was formed by six of the campaigning groups at this meeting.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In 1981, the 34th World Health Assembly (WHA), the decision-making body for WHO, adopted Resolution WHA34.22 which includes the International Code of Marketing of Breast-milk Substitutes.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The Code covers infant formula and other milk products, foods and beverages, when marketed or otherwise represented to be suitable as a partial or total replacement of breast milk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] It bans the promotion of breast milk substitutes and gives health workers the responsibility for advising parents.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] It limits manufacturing companies to the provision of scientific and factual information to health workers and sets forth labeling requirements.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In 1984, boycott coordinators met with Nestlé, which agreed to create an independent agency, the Nestlé Infant Formula Audit Commission (IFAC), and to sign an agreement where they pledged to fully implement the Code.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The boycott was then officially suspended.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In 1988, a second phase of the boycott started as IBFAN alleged that formula companies were flooding health facilities in the developing world with free and low-cost supplies, and the boycott was relaunched the following year.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In May 1999, a ruling against Nestlé was issued by the UK Advertising Standards Authority (ASA).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Nestlé claimed in an anti-boycott advertisement that it markets infant formula "ethically and responsibly".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The ASA found that Nestlé could not support this nor other claims in the face of evidence provided by the campaigning group Baby Milk Action.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In November 2000, the European Parliament invited IBFAN, UNICEF, and Nestlé to present evidence to a public hearing before the Development and Cooperation Committee.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Evidence was presented by the IBFAN group from Pakistan and UNICEF's legal officer commented on Nestlé's failure to bring its policies into line with the World Health Assembly Resolutions.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Nestlé declined an invitation to attend, claiming scheduling conflicts, although it sent a representative of the auditing company it had commissioned to produce a report on its Pakistan operation.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Throughout the years, Nestlé has claimed that it is in full compliance with the International Code.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In 2001, for example, Peter Brabeck-Letmathe, at the time CEO of Nestlé, stated: "we also carry out annual audits on WHO Code compliance with a sample of Nestlé companies, and we investigate any substantiated claims made by those who believe we have broken the Code....
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] If we find that the Code has been deliberately violated, we take disciplinary action." The company maintained that many of the allegations are unsubstantiated, out of date, or use IBFAN's own non-standard interpretation of the Code.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In May 2011, the debate over Nestlé's unethical marketing of infant formula was relaunched in the Asia-Pacific region.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Nineteen leading Laos-based international NGOs, including Save the Children, Oxfam, CARE International, Plan International and World Vision have launched a boycott of Nestlé and written an open letter to the company.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Among other unethical practices, the NGOs criticised the lack of labelling in Laos and the provision of incentives to doctors and nurses to promote the use of infant formula.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] An independent audit of Nestlé's marketing practices in Laos was commissioned by Nestlé and carried out by Bureau Veritas in late 2011.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The audit found that "the requirements of the WHO Code and Lao PDR Decree are well embedded throughout the business", but that "promotional materials in 4% of the retail outlets visited" violated either the Lao PDR Decree or the WHO Code.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In a 2018 study, the National Bureau of Economic Research (NBER) estimated that 10,870,000 infants had died between 1960 and 2015 as a result of Nestlé baby formula used by "mothers [in low and middle-income countries] without clean water sources", with deaths peaking at 212,000 in 1981.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In 2024, a report by Swiss nonprofit Public Eye and IBFAN stated that Nestlé adds more sugar to baby food sold in lower- and middle-income countries compared to healthier versions sold in affluent markets.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Nestlé also officially states on their website that it "follow[s] the WHO Code as implemented by national governments everywhere in the world".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The company states that it updates its marketing policy, that it reports on compliance on an annual basis, and that it set up a whistleblower scheme.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Nestlé states that it is "committed not to interfere with mothers' desire to breastfeed and to protect them from inappropriate marketing practices by actively supporting breastfeeding".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Critics state that Nestlé continues to be accused of malpractice.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Data from 2020 indicates that 136 WHO member states had established some legal measures related to the Code from 1981, however, only few fully reflect the Code.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The report indicates a gap in many countries' legislation.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] IBFAN continues to be an international network, encompassing more than 270 groups in over 160 countries who push for implementations of the marketing of breast-milk substitutes Code and relevant resolutions.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The overall goal remains: marketing baby food should not have negative impacts on infants' health.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In 2024, a new controversy arose when Nestlé was criticized for adding sugar and honey to infant milk and cereal products in certain countries.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] An episode of the TV show *The Mark Thomas Comedy Product* produced by the British Channel Four in 1999 investigated the boycott and Nestlé's practices concerning baby milk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] Mark Thomas attempted to find evidence for claims against Nestlé and to speak to heads of the company.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In one portion of the show he received a tin of baby milk from Mozambique.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] 33 languages and dialects are recognised in Mozambique.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] However, only about 30% of the population can speak it.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In 2001, comedian Robert Newman and actress Emma Thompson called for a boycott of the Perrier Comedy Award, because Perrier is owned by Nestlé.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] An alternative competition called the Tap Water Awards was set up the following year.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] In 2002, authors Germaine Greer and Jim Crace withdrew from the Hay Festival in protest over Nestlé's sponsorship of the event.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] A 2007 article in *The Guardian* highlighted marketing practices by Nestlé in Bangladesh that were perceived as aggressive.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/1977-nestlé-boycott] The 2014 film *Tigers* is based on 1997 Pakistan Nestle infant formula controversy.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The **2008 Chinese milk scandal** was a significant food safety incident in China.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The scandal involved Sanlu Group's milk and infant formula along with other food materials and components being adulterated with the chemical melamine, which resulted in kidney stones and other kidney damage in infants.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The chemical was used to increase the nitrogen content of diluted milk, giving it the appearance of higher protein content in order to pass quality control testing.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] 300,000 affected children were identified, among which 54,000 were hospitalized, according to the latest report in January 2009.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The deaths of six babies were officially concluded to be related to the contaminated milk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The timeline of the scandal dated back to December 2007, when Sanlu began to receive complaints about kidney stones.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] An early complaint was made on 20 May 2008, when a mother posted online after she learnt that Sanlu had donated the milk she had been complaining about to the orphans of the 2008 Sichuan earthquake.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Also on 20 May, the problem was raised at Sanlu's Board meeting for the first time and they ordered multiple third-party tests.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The culprit, melamine, was undetected in the tests until 1 August.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] New Zealand dairy giant Fonterra, which owned a 43% stake in Sanlu, were alerted to the contamination on 2 August.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Fonterra alerted the New Zealand government and the NZ government confronted the Chinese government on 8 September.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Chinese government made the scandal public on 13 September.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] After the initial focus on Sanlu, further government inspections revealed that products from 21 other companies were also tainted, including those from Arla Foods–Mengniu, Yili, and Yashili.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] While more and more cases reached hospitals around the nation from December 2007, the first report to the government by any hospital was made on 16 July.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The issue raised concerns about food safety and political corruption in China and damaged the reputation of the country's food exports.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The World Health Organization called the incident "deplorable" and at least 11 foreign countries halted all imports of Chinese dairy products.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The former chairwoman of China's Sanlu dairy was sentenced to life in prison.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In late October 2008, similar adulteration with melamine was discovered in eggs and possibly other foods.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The source was traced to melamine being added to animal feed, despite a ban imposed in June 2007 following the scandal over pet food ingredients exported to the United States.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Melamine is used to manufacture melamine-formaldehyde resin, a type of plastic known for its flame-retardant properties and commonly employed in countertops, dry-erase boards, etc.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] It has also been employed as a non-protein nitrogen, appearing in soy meal, corn gluten meal and cottonseed meal used in cattle feed.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Melamine is known to cause kidney failure and kidney stones in humans and animals when it reacts with cyanuric acid inside the body.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The use of melamine in food production is not approved by the World Health Organization (WHO) or national authorities.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Melamine is nitrogen-rich, so it is sometimes illegally added to food products to increase their apparent protein content.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Kjeldahl and Dumas methods used to test for protein levels fail to distinguish between nitrogen in melamine and naturally occurring nitrogen in amino acids, allowing the protein levels to be falsified.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Introduced into milk, it can help conceal fraudulent dilution with water.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Melamine adulteration of food products also made headlines when pet food was recalled in Europe and the U.S. in 2007.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) said melamine may be found "in a variety of milk and milk products at varying levels, from low ppb to ppm ranges".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] One academic suggested cyromazine, a melamine derivative pesticide commonly used in China for a long time, is absorbed into plants as melamine; it may therefore have long been present in products such as poultry, eggs, fish, and dairy products.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] It is not known where in the supply chain the melamine was added to the milk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The chemical is not water-soluble, and must be mixed with formaldehyde or another chemical before it can be dissolved in milk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Because of poor animal husbandry, production and storage and the demand for milk far outstripping supplies, the use of other potentially harmful chemical additives such as preservatives and hydrogen peroxide has been reported by independent media as being commonplace.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Quality tests can be falsified with additives: peroxide is added to prevent milk from going bad; industrial vegetable oil is emulsified and added to boost fat levels; whey is used to increase lactose content.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] However, the procurement chain is also implicated, as milk agents are often politically well-connected.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Farmers report salespeople had, for years, been visiting farms in dairy areas hawking "protein powder" additives, which would often be delivered in unmarked brown paper bags of 25 kilograms (55 lb) each.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Thus, farmers either added melamine contaminant unwittingly, or turned a blind eye to milk adulteration to ensure their milk was not rejected.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The big dairy producers were complicit in producing "test-tube milk".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 17 September 2008, Health Minister Chen Zhu stated tainted milk formula had "sickened more than 6,200 children, and that more than 1,300 others, mostly newborns, remain hospitalized with 158 suffering from acute kidney failure".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] By 23 September, about 54,000 children were reported to be sick and four had died.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] An additional 10,000 cases were reported from the provinces by 27 September.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] A World Health Organization official said 82% of the children made ill were 2 years of age or below.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Hong Kong Centre for Food Safety said that 99 per cent of the victims were aged under 3 years.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Ten Hong Kong children were diagnosed with kidney problems, at least four cases were detected in Macau, and six in Taiwan.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Non-human casualties included a lion cub and two baby orangutans which had been fed Sanlu infant formula at Hangzhou Zoo.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The government said on 8 October it would no longer issue updated figures "because it is not an infectious disease, so it's not absolutely necessary for us to announce it to the public".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Reuters compiled figures reported by local media across the country, and said the toll stood at nearly 94,000 at the end of September, excluding municipalities.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Notably, 13,459 children had been affected in Gansu, Reuters quoted Xinhua saying Henan had reported over 30,000 cases, and Hebei also had nearly 16,000 cases.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In late October, the government announced health officials had surveyed 300,000 Beijing families with children less than 3 years old.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] It disclosed approximately 74,000 families had a child who had been fed melamine-tainted milk, but did not reveal how many of those children had fallen ill as a result.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Because of the many months before the scandal was exposed, media suggested the official figures were likely to be understated.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Kidney stones in infants started being reported in several parts of China in the two years prior.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] A number of yet-to-be-officially-acknowledged cases were reported by the media.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] However, those deaths without an official verdict may be denied compensation.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On characterisation and treatment of urinary stones in affected infants, the *New England Journal of Medicine* printed an editorial in March 2009, along with reports on cases from Beijing, Hong Kong and Taipei.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Urinary calculi specimens were collected from 15 cases treated in Beijing and were analysed as unknown objects for their components at Beijing Institute of Microchemistry using infrared spectroscopy, nuclear magnetic resonance, and high-performance liquid chromatography.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The result of the analyses showed the calculi were composed of melamine and uric acid, and the molecular ratio of uric acid to melamine was around 2:1.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In a study published in 2010, researchers from Peking University studying ultrasound images of infants who fell ill in the 2008 contamination found while most children in a rural Chinese area recovered, 12 per cent still showed kidney abnormalities six months later.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] "The potential for long-term complications after exposure to melamine remains a serious concern", the report said.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Contaminated products found in the China AQSIS tests include baby formula products produced by the following companies, in order of highest concentration found.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The scandal began with revelations of contamination of Sanlu milk products.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The New Zealand dairy cooperative Fonterra, which owned a 43% stake in Sanlu, said they were alerted to melamine contamination on 2 August (almost a month before the issue became public), and have said to have pushed hard for a full public recall.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Although there was an immediate trade recall, Fonterra said that local administrators refused an official recall.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] A Fonterra director had given Sanlu management a document detailing the European Union's permitted levels of melamine, but Fonterra chief executive Andrew Ferrier has stated that at no time did Fonterra say small amounts of melamine were acceptable.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] From 2005 to 2006, an agent, Jiang Weisuo, from Shaanxi Jinqiao Dairy Company in northern China reportedly publicly discussed his fears about unauthorised substances being added to competitors' milk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The paediatrician, who specifically asked the AQSIQ to refer his observations to epidemiologists, was asked to refer his query to the health department.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In June, Jiangsu media reported a two-month surge in the number of babies diagnosed with kidney disease; in July, a parent of a sick baby in Hunan questioned Sanlu's powdered milk and complained to the AQSIQ.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Gansu Province sent a report to the Ministry of Health on 16 July to alert that one local hospital had identified an increase in the incidence of kidney ailments among babies in the months earlier, and that most victims had consumed Sanlu's baby formula.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The health ministry sent investigators to Gansu in early August.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Fonterra notified the New Zealand government on 5 September and three days later, Prime Minister Helen Clark had Beijing officials alerted directly.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] News reports began circulating in China on 9 September, and the news was broken internationally by Reuters the following day.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The state-controlled media report did not initially identify the company involved.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Posts on Chinese social portal Tianya named Sanlu as the culprit, which Sanlu denied.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] According to a State Council investigation, Sanlu had known about infants made sick by its products as early as December 2007, but no testing was performed until June 2008.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] It said leading government officials in Shijiazhuang city had failed to report the contamination to provincial and state authorities (until 9 September) in violation of rules on reporting major incidents involving food safety.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] According to the *People's Daily*, on 2 August, Sanlu asked the Shijiazhuang city government to assist them in controlling the media's reporting of the recall.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] According to accounts confirmed by media reports and health officials, the company tried to buy off critics and cover up the contamination.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In a memo dated 11 August, Beijing-based public relations agency Teller International advised Sanlu to seek cooperation with major search engines to censor negative information.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The agency reportedly had repeatedly contacted key account staff at Baidu and proposed a ¥3 million (US$440,000) budget to screen all negative news.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] After the memo began circulating on the internet, Baidu denounced, in a communiqué on 13 September 2008, the approaches by said agency on several occasions, saying the proposal was firmly rejected, as it violated their corporate principles of unbiased and transparent reporting.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] New Zealand Prime Minister Helen Clark said that she believed the Chinese government had been inclined to try to solve the problem quietly, without a recall.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Central government denied issuing this guidance.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Hebei provincial vice-governor said his administration was only notified by Shijiazhuang on 8 September.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] However, a journalist at *Southern Weekend* wrote an investigative report in late July for publication about infants who had fallen ill after consuming baby formula from Sanlu.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Six weeks later, senior editor Fu Jianfeng made a post on his personal blog stating that this report had been suppressed by authorities because of the imminent Beijing Olympics.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] While this was happening, Sanlu was honoured in a national award campaign called "30 Years: Brands that Have Changed the Lives of Chinese".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The press release on the award, written by a senior public relations manager at Sanlu, passed as news content on *People's Daily* and in other media.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 15 September, the company issued a public apology for the contaminated powdered milk; Sanlu was ordered to halt production, and to destroy all unsold and recalled products.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Authorities reportedly seized 2,176 tons of powdered milk in Sanlu's warehouses.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] An estimated 9,000 tons of product had been recalled.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Shijiazhuang Mayor Ji Chuntang resigned on 17 September.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Li Changjiang, minister in charge of the AQSIQ, was forced to resign on 22 September after the State Council inquest concluded he was responsible for the "negligence in supervision".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Investigators also blamed the Shijiazhuang government.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Local Party Secretary Wu Xianguo was fired on the same day.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Sanlu general manager Tian Wenhua was charged under Articles 144 and 150 of the criminal code.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] A spokesman for the Hebei Provincial Public Security Department said police had arrested 12 milk dealers and suppliers who allegedly sold contaminated milk to Sanlu, and six people were charged with selling melamine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Three hundred kg (700 lb) of suspicious chemicals, including 223 kg (492 lb) of melamine, were confiscated.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Among those arrested were two brothers who ran a milk collection centre in Hebei for allegedly supplying three tonnes of adulterated milk daily to the dairy; the owner of another collection centre which resold seven tons of milk a day to Sanlu, was arrested, and his operation was shut down.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Zhang Yujun (alias Zhang Haitao), a former dairy farmer from Hebei, produced more than 600 tons of a "protein powder" mixture of melamine and maltodextrin from September 2007 to August 2008.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] He and eight other traders, dairy farm owners and milk purchasers who bought the powder from him were arrested in early October, bringing the total to 36.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] During the week of 22 December 2008, 17 people involved in producing, selling, buying and adding melamine in raw milk went on trial.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Tian Wenhua, former Sanlu general manager, and three other company executives appeared in court in Shijiazhuang, charged with producing and selling milk contaminated with melamine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] According to *Xinhua*, Tian pleaded guilty, and told the court she learned about the tainted milk complaints from consumers in mid-May.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] She then apparently headed a working team to handle the case, but did not report to the Shijiazhuang city government until 2 August.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Intermediate People's Court in Shijiazhuang sentenced Zhang Yujun and Geng Jinping to death, and Tian Wenhua to life in prison, on 22 January 2009.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Zhang was convicted for producing 800 tons of the contaminated powder, Geng for producing and selling toxic food.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Geng Jinping managed a milk production center which supplied milk to Sanlu Group and other dairies.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The *China Daily* reported Geng had knelt on the courtroom floor and begged the victim's families for forgiveness during the trial.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The court also sentenced Sanlu deputy general managers Wang Yuliang and Hang Zhiqi to fifteen years and eight years in jail, respectively, and former manager Wu Jusheng to five years.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Zhang Yujun and Geng Jinping were executed on 24 November 2009.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Tian Wenhua received several sentence reductions for good conduct over the years.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In 2011, her life term was reduced to 19 years.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Further reductions have since lowered that sentence to 15 years and three months.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The value of the company plunged as a result of the scandal.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 24 September, Fonterra announced it had written down the carrying value of its investment by NZ$139 million (two-thirds), reflecting the costs of product recall and the impairment of the 'Sanlu' brand because of the "criminal contamination of milk".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] By 27 September, *China Daily* reported Sanlu was close to bankruptcy, and might be taken over by the Beijing Sanyuan Foods Company.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The company is also facing lawsuits from parents (see *Anger at Sanlu*).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 25 December, Shijiazhuang court accepted a creditor's bankruptcy petition against Sanlu.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Media commentators expected the Sanlu distribution network to be sold.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 16 September, the AQSIQ released test of samples from 491 batches of products sold by all 109 companies producing baby formula.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] It said all 11 samples from Sanlu failed the melamine test.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Sanlu, whose products sell at half the price of equivalents on the market, recorded the highest levels of contamination among all the samples tested, at 2,563 mg/kg or parts per million ("ppm").
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Tainted samples were found among 21 other suppliers, where concentrations ranged from 0.09 to 619.00 ppm.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] There was melamine contamination in 10% of liquid milk samples from Mengniu and Yili, and 6% of those from Bright Dairy.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On discovery of contamination, the three major producers were all stripped of their status as 'Chinese national brands'.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Yili, Mengniu and Bright Dairy & Food Co. recalled tainted powdered milk and apologised in separate statements.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Mengniu recalled all its baby formula, and trading in its shares on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange was suspended on 17 September.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Shares in other dairy companies fell strongly the next day.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Mengniu's CFO attempted to reassure consumers by offering a no-quibble refund on all products, and by drinking liquid milk in front of reporters in Hong Kong.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] He also said that its export products were less likely to be contaminated.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 30 September, the AQSIQ announced test results of a further 265 batches of powdered milk produced by 154 different companies prior to 14 September, where it found 31 batches produced by 20 domestic dairy companies were tainted with melamine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 1 December, China's Ministry of Health issued an update, saying nearly 300,000 babies were sickened after consuming melamine-contaminated infant formula.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The State Council ordered the testing of product of all dairy producers, and to this end, some 5,000 inspectors were dispatched.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Chinese market has grown at an average annual rate of 23% since 2000.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In 2006, milk production reached 30 million tons, ten times the volume of a decade before.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] It was valued at some ¥122 billion (US$18 billion) in 2007, and consumers had severely lost confidence in the industry.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The events have exposed the often-incestuous relationship between local business and local government.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The scandal has also highlighted structural problems of inadequate production volume, inherent quality issues, and poor production methods.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Inner Mongolia region produces over one-fourth of China's milk, and Mengniu and Yili have invested millions to establish state-of-the-art dairy facilities in its capital, Hohhot.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The companies still rely on small-scale farmers for over 90% of their production because of the capacity constraint of the modern facilities.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Both companies were said by farmers and agents to have habitually purchased milk which failed quality tests, for only two-thirds the normal price.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] A new policy was put in place on 17 September to stop that practice.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Consumer panic resulting from the contaminated milk lessened demand for dairy products, causing hardship to more than 2 million Chinese farmers who had nowhere to sell their milk and no means by which to support their dairy cows.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Farmers reportedly poured away milk and faced selling cows to a buyerless market.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Since the scandal erupted, sales have fallen by 30–40% on a comparative basis, according to the Chinese Dairy Association.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The Association estimates the financial effect of the order of ¥20 billion, and forecasts that confidence may take up to two years to be fully restored.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In an effort to prop up sales and retain their market share, dairy firms have cancelled their common accord not to use promotions to fight the sales decline: substantial discounts (including BOGOF), free gifts and other point of sale incentives were being offered to shoppers.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Their new products are conspicuously labelled "safety inspection passed" to allay consumer fears.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Mengniu-Arla, a joint-venture between Danish/Swedish co-operative Arla Foods and Mengniu halted production on 16 September 2008 after three of 28 tests taken from Mengniu showed traces of melamine; the contaminated batches had been recalled.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Mengniu, milk supplier to Starbucks, was replaced by Vitasoy when the coffee retailer eschewed milk in favour of soya milk in its China operations.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] KFC also suspended selling Mengniu milk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Seoul-headquartered Lotte Group, a major snacks maker, recalled its Koala's March cookies in Hong Kong and Macau because of contamination, and promised to "look deeply into all the details of the manufacturing process" to preserve customer confidence.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The range was also ordered off Dutch and Slovak shelves.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Other products were seized when samples tested positive in Malta.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 29 September, British confectionery group Cadbury recalled all chocolate products made in its Chinese factories due to concerns about melamine contamination, affecting products intended for markets in China, Taiwan, Hong Kong, Japan, Korea and Australia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Tests in Hong Kong found amounts of melamine in China-made Dairy Milk products which exceeded safety regulations.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 30 September, Unilever recalled its Lipton milk tea powder after the company's internal checks found traces of melamine in the Chinese powdered milk used as an ingredient.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Heinz recalled cases of baby cereal in Hong Kong after discovering they contained melamine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Nestlé's factory in Heilongjiang was also implicated: the Taiwanese Department of Health forced the delisting of six *Neslac* and *KLIM* products on 2 October for containing minute traces of melamine, although the minister said they did not pose a significant health risk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Since the milk crisis broke, Nestlé says it has sent 20 specialists from Switzerland to five of its Chinese plants to strengthen chemical testing.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 31 October, it announced the opening of a $10.2 million Beijing research and development centre, to "serve as the base and the reference in food safety for Nestlé in Greater China".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Nestlé Chief Technology Officer said the centre was equipped with "highly sophisticated analytical tools for detecting trace amounts of residues and undesirable compounds like melamine or veterinary drugs or natural toxins".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] There were concerns dairy products consumed during the 2008 Summer Olympics may have been contaminated.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Li Changjiang, the then Director of AQSIQ reassured the international community that all the food, including dairy products, was indeed safe.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] PRC Customs said exports of dairy products and eggs in 2007 were valued at US$359 million, a year-on-year increase of 90 per cent.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Since the news of the melamine contamination began to circulate, at least 25 countries stopped importing Chinese dairy products.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The scandal led to an erosion of trust in locally produced infant formula and from then on, many Shenzhen residents and parallel traders travelled across the border to purchase powdered milk from Hong Kong shops.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Lower confidence in mainland Chinese production, combined with the relaxation of visa requirements for mainland residents, had resulted in shortages of infant formula in Hong Kong for an extended time.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Because of a great public outcry, the Import and Export (General) (Amendment) Regulation 2013 was passed in Hong Kong, prohibiting the unlicensed export of powdered formula, including milk and soya milk powder for infants and children under 36 months.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Although the Hong Kong government imposed a strict 2-can limit on the export of infant formula in March 2013, spurred price differentials caused by sales tax on the mainland and lax customs, trafficking activity including for powdered milk has continued, exacerbating the Hong Kong-Mainland conflict.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The catchment area for traffickers spread from Fan Ling and Sheung Shui southward to Yuen Long and Tuen Mun, causing localist camp such as Civic Passion and Hong Kong Indigenous to take to the streets in direct action in 2015.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] On 25 September 2008, the EU announced a ban on imports of baby food containing Chinese milk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In the United States of America, which was otherwise unaffected by the scares, the US distributor of White Rabbit candies recalled the product when samples found in Hartford showed traces of melamine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The candy's maker and subsidiary of Bright Foods, Guan Sheng Yuan, issued a recall to the 50 countries to which it exported.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] Food and Drug Administration said while food containing melamine below 2.5 parts per million generally did not raise concerns, its scientists were "currently unable to establish any level of melamine and melamine-related compounds in infant formula that does not raise public health concerns".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] In late November, after the FDA found traces of melamine in one Nestle and one Mead Johnson infant product, the FDA concluded melamine or cyanuric acid alone, "at or below 1 part per million in infant formula do not raise public health concerns" in babies.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p01] The United States Food and Drug Administration opened its first overseas inspection offices in November 2008, with bureaus in Shanghai, Beijing and Guangzhou.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) warned that children who ate large amounts of confectionery and biscuits with high milk content could theoretically be consuming melamine at more than three times above prescribed EU safety limits (0.5 mg/kg of body weight).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The EFSA said children with a mean consumption of products such as milk toffee, biscuits and chocolate containing contaminated powdered milk would not be at risk, and adults would not be at risk even in the worst-case scenarios.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The World Health Organization, which was only notified on 11 September, asked Beijing why it took so many months for the scandal to become public, and to establish whether failure was deliberate or due to ignorance.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] WHO's representative in China, Hans Troedsson, said the issue of who knew what and when was critical, because knowledge would be the distinction between ignorance and neglect.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Following a spate of mass national bans, the WHO urged national food safety authorities on 25 September to test Chinese dairy products for health risks before placing import bans or recalls.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 26 September, the WHO warned health officials to look out for tainted dairy products imported from China.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] International Food Safety Authorities (INFOSAN), a network organized by WHO and the Food and Agriculture Organization, suggested that countries should focus on smuggled formula.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] WHO referred to the incident as one of the largest food safety events it has had to deal with, and stated it would be difficult to restore the confidence of Chinese consumers in baby formula.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] It saw regulation failing to keep pace with the rapid development of the food and industrial production as opening the gates to all types of misbehaviour and malfeasance.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The spokesman said the scale of the problem proved it was "clearly not an isolated accident, [but] a large-scale intentional activity to deceive consumers for simple, basic, short-term profits".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] WHO Director-General Margaret Chan reminded Chinese mothers that breastfeeding was the best way to provide nutrition to infants while avoiding a risk of melamine exposure.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] She noted that the scandal showed "the impact and power of globalisation" in food distribution and highlighted "the importance of seamless cooperation from farm to consumer".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The case has brought anger and resentment towards milk producers and sowed uncertainty and confusion amongst the population.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Queues formed outside Sanlu's offices for refunds.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] As has been increasingly common practice, web users vented their anger on internet bulletin boards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Prevalent food scares have increased the number of online parodies circulated by netizens.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Before the government began offering free medical treatment, some parents had reportedly spent small fortunes on medical care for their sick children.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Children who fell ill before the scandal broke on 12 September were not entitled to free medical care offered by the State.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Parents of two such victims, one from Henan and one from Guangdong, filed writs against Sanlu despite government pressure.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Parents of the Henan child had claimed ¥150,000 for medical, travel and other expenses incurred after their child developed kidney stones.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 20 October, the parents of one baby who died from contaminated milk appealed to New Zealand for justice on TV ONE.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] A total of nine cases were filed against Sanlu in Shijiazhuang.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Following weeks of discussions, and in the absence of a compensation plan, a group of 15 lawyers filed a class-action lawsuit on behalf of 100 families against Sanlu, seeking medical and other expenses as well as compensation for trauma and for death of an offspring.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Resentment increased towards the country's leaders due to the perception that they were not troubled by the food security turmoil faced by ordinary citizens.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Poorer consumers reliant on local infant formula, which was approximately half the price of imported brands, had been left without alternatives to feed their children.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Many had lost faith in local brands, with others unsure of which brands were safe.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Supermarket shelves had been swept bare from product recalls.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Shops in Hong Kong reported a rush for imported formula from cross-border shoppers, with some retailers reportedly rationing their stocks.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Some mainlanders were also reportedly rushing to import infant formula from Kinmen.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Wet nurses enjoyed a resurgence in popularity in major cities.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Some media reports have documented that Chinese sailors and expatriates have been buying local dairy produce in Australia to send back to relatives in China.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] It had been estimated in 2018 that up to 80% to 90% of infant formula purchased in Australia was destined for China.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Following widespread complaints and appeals by exasperated Australian parents unable to find formula for their children, Coles supermarkets resorted to locking baby formula tins away behind the Service Counter, like tobacco products, in order to regulate their sale.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The two major supermarkets, Coles and Woolworths, placed a two item limit on baby formula purchases to curb the growing practice of bulk purchasing by predominantly Chinese customers known as *daigou*, or "personal shoppers".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] These people would often travel in large, organised groups from supermarket to supermarket, clearing the shelves of baby formula, then make substantial profits by sending the formula to China to be sold at a significant markup.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Protesters fearful at reunification blamed the Kuomintang for the melamine scare, and criticised it for failing to stand up to China over the contamination.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] One citizen voiced concern that President Ma Ying-jeou's promise for closer ties with China would bring in more tainted products to Taiwan.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The Minister of the Department of Health, Lin Fang-yue, was heavily criticised for raising the legally acceptable limit of melamine in food products from zero to 2.5 ppm.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The public outcry subsequent to the move forced Lin to resign.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] His successor, Yeh Ching-chuan, announced a return to the original zero-tolerance policy to melamine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] AQSIQ announced the revocation of all exemptions from inspection previously granted to dairy producers, who were asked to cease citing the privilege in their advertisements.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The State Council ordered an overhaul of the dairy industry, and promised to provide free medical care to those affected.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Formally, the State Council released its initial findings, and a top-level official apology of the incident both came on 21 September.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Wen Jiabao apologised while visiting victims in hospitals.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 6 October 2008, putting the blame on "illegal production and greed", the country's "chaotic dairy production and distribution order", and the "gravely absent supervision" for the crisis, the State Council announced new dairy industry regulations.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On November 19, 2008, the State Council promulgated the "China Dairy Industry Reorganization and Revitalization Plan" to rectify the chaos in China's dairy industry.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 9 October 2008, in an attempt to control the damage to Chinese dairy exports, officials at a World Trade Organization meeting insisted that contamination had been "accidental", directly contradicting the WHO observations.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Chinese trade representatives criticised countries which have imposed blanket bans on Chinese food products.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] They urged member states to base import restrictions on scientific risk assessments, and to use official WTO notification mechanisms.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 11 October, Deputy Health minister Liu Qian stated that all the foreign companies' application for compensation for dairy products recall would be dealt with on a commercial basis, although government may use diplomatic channels if necessary, if problems were encountered.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] According to a senior quality inspectorate official, the government aimed to establish nearly 400 product testing centres within the next two years, and 80 of these would be food testing centres.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Working groups were established in nearly every single province in order to set up new food testing centres and replace outdated equipment.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 24 September 2008, China's newly appointed AQSIQ chief Wang Yong said that the government would "carry out 'forceful' measures to deal with the chemical contamination", and stated that inspectors had removed 7,000 tonnes of melamine-contaminated dairy products from shops all over China.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The ministry was reported to have investigated 98 dairy producers and farms, banned 151 illegal companies and indicted three manufacturers for feed containing melamine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] During an investigation into melamine contamination at Yili and Mengniu in Hohhot, police arrested six more people for allegedly selling and mixing melamine into raw milk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The AQSIQ announced on 5 October that all tests showed all milk produced after 14 September were free from contamination.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The General Administration of Quality Supervision, Inspection and Quarantine stated all dairy products made before 14 September will be tested for melamine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] They gave notice to all supermarkets, shops, and all city, town and village-level vendors to urgently remove and seal up all powdered milk and liquid milk made before 14 September, pending further testing.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] A researcher at the Chinese Centre for Disease Control and Prevention said that any amount exceeding 1 ppm would give reason to suspect its presence was intentional.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 16 September, the AQSIQ tests on baby milk powder produced by 109 companies showed 69 batches from 22 companies to be melamine-contaminated; the State Council attempted to reassure that formula produced by most companies in China was safe.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 16 September, the AQSIQ published results of tests on 408 liquid milk producers, and found "most dairy products were safe to drink", although the test results showed nearly 10 percent of batches from Mengniu, Yili and Bright were contaminated.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] To demonstrate that its emergency measures had been effective, the Ministry of Agriculture said the rate of raw milk dumping because of the contamination scandal has decreased from 23.6% on 22 September to 4.6% on 1 October.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] During the scandal, China's media was ordered to tone down coverage of the unfolding scandal to prevent unrest.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] News editors were told to adhere to the official copy provided by China's state news agency, *Xinhua News Agency*, and to emphasize other news instead.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] China Central Television shifted its reporting emphasis to the launch of Shenzhou VII, with the announcement of the AQSIQ test results relegated to the final item on the CCTV evening news.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] As a result of media suppression, Chinese consumers were ill-informed about the extent of global recalls.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] According to Chinese journalists, discussion of the causes of the crisis, government responsibility, questions about government complicity with dairy companies, was forbidden.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 2 January, a website created by individuals protesting against Sanlu was also blocked by the authorities.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] A group of parents whose children were rendered ill by melamine-contaminated milk held a news conference to draw attention to the plight of their sick children; five were allegedly detained by police and taken to a labour camp outside Beijing.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] In 2012, Jiang Weisuo, a 44-year-old general manager of a dairy products plant in Shaanxi province, was rumoured to have been murdered in Xi'an city.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] It was Jiang who had first alerted authorities to the scandal.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] According to the Xi'an Evening News, Jiang died in hospital on 12 November from knife wounds inflicted by his wife, Yang Ping, but the purported murder by his wife was subsequently reported to be incorrect.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] A group of 90 lawyers from Hebei, Henan and Shandong—the three worst affected provinces—had made *pro bono* offers to assist victims, and a list of their names was published.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Organisers of the group declared that they had come under pressure from officials to not get involved in the issue.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The Beijing Lawyers' Association, a part of the Communist Party apparatus, asked its members "to put faith in the party and government".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Other members of the group have reportedly received less subtle requests.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Authorities are said to fear social unrest if lawsuits were unleashed.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Pro-Beijing Hong Kong journal *Ta Kung Pao* reported that central authorities, fearful of the effect of mass lawsuits, held a meeting with lawyers' groups on 14 September, asking them to "act together, and help maintain stability".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Chang Boyang, one of the group of volunteer lawyers, said he had filed one suit in Guangdong against Sanlu on behalf of the parents of one victim, and another suit in Henan.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] According to Chang, the justice department of Henan ordered 14 Henan lawyers to drop their cases and "follow the arrangements set out by the government".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] An official said that central government had issued instructions placing the cases on hold, pending a decision on how to handle the cases in a unified manner.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Furthermore, that court was instructed not to give any written replies or accept Sanlu-related cases in the meantime.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Stratfor believed that the act of adulterating milk and baby food in full knowledge of potentially severe sanctions, including execution, seemed like "an act of desperation".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] It noted that in 2008 dairy farmers became squeezed by growing costs of livestock, feed, facilities, and government-imposed price caps.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Mengniu's share price had fallen 12% since October 2007 because of higher costs of raw milk (due partly to rising costs of cattle feed) and price controls—anti-inflation measures targeted at the dairy sector announced on 16 January.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Milk suppliers accordingly resorted to subtler cost-cutting methods to preserve diminishing profits.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Joseph Sternberg of *The Wall Street Journal* said that Beijing's failures of food-safety act are "much more pernicious, and disgraceful, than at first it appears ... [not only has this] milk poisoned thousands of infants with melamine, it also poisons the society at large with fear".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Lawyer Bill Marler, speaking at a food safety conference in Beijing, said that this food scare has harmed the "made in China" brand abroad.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] An op-ed in *The New York Times* compared this to the "swill milk scandal" in New York in the 1850s in which 8,000 children reportedly died when cows were fed swill and the milk produced was then whitened with plaster of Paris, thickened with starch and eggs, and hued with molasses.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] An article published in the *San Francisco Chronicle* likened the regulatory failures of the milk scandal to the distressed assets in the subprime mortgage crisis, and questioned whether regulators in either case ever understood or truly monitored the extent of the danger.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 10 November 2008 issue of the Singaporean newspaper *Today*, Bill Durodié, then a senior fellow at the S.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The structure of the Chinese government was criticized for contributing to the scandal.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] *Time* magazine cited analysts saying the party's need to maintain control of the economy and of information undermines the independence of any regulatory system.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] One analyst, Willy Lam, a Senior Fellow at The Jamestown Foundation, indicated that CCP's pervasive control over political and economic resources has resulted in a lack of accountability in government systems.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] A Beijing-based consultancy, Dragonomics, concurred that "the problem was rooted in the Communist Party's continued involvement in pricing control, company management and the flow of information".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Independent regulation was lacking or ineffective as local industries were so intertwined with local officialdom.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Access Asia, a Shanghai-based consumer consultancy, said Fonterra was an example of western executives in China "believ[ing] advice in business books that they must avoid making their local partners 'lose face' at all costs".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] It suggested that Fonterra paid the price for this both financially and in damage to their reputation.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] David Bandurski, journalist and researcher at China Media Project, criticised the state's control of the media for suppressing "information critical to the well-being of ordinary Chinese".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] He asserted that increased press freedom needs to be a component of any strategy to deal with this and other future food-security lapses in China.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Bandurski cited warnings on 9 October 2008 issues of *Nanfang Daily* and the *Information Times* for consumers to be aware of that problematic dairy stock (that produced before 14 September) have reappeared in some stores under cover of aggressive promotions.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Former senior party official Bao Tong said "the more dark secrets are exposed, the better.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] You can't cure the disease, or save the Chinese people, until you get to the root of the problem." "If the Chinese government tries to play down this incident, there will be no social stability in China, let alone harmony ...
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] As a reaction to and comment on the scandal, Chinese artist and video animation producer Pi San created "Little Rabbit, Be Good" as part of his popular Kuang Kuang video series.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Though officially banned or forbidden by the Chinese government, clever use of Chinese web services such as Baidu allows Chinese citizens to access this and many other forbidden materials.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] This daigou activity has been facilitated by the Chinese Navy and its warships.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The search widened when some manufacturers tested positive despite reportedly not using Chinese milk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Japanese and South Korean authorities' tests on imported powdered eggs from China found melamine contamination.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Japan found melamine in frozen fried chicken imported from China.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The South Korean supplies were traced to two companies in Dalian.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 26 October, Hong Kong authorities discovered 4.7ppm melamine in eggs from Dalian.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Hong Kong Secretary for Food and Health, York Chow, suspected the melamine came from feed given to the chickens that laid the eggs.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 29 October, Hong Kong authorities discovered a third batch of eggs containing excessive melamine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The Taiwanese Department of Health said that six batches of protein powder from Jilin and Dalian were found to contain 1.90 to 5.03ppm of melamine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Agriculture officials speculated that adulterated feed given to hens could explain melamine in eggs.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The Web sites of *Xinhua* and *People's Daily* both carried a story from the *Nanfang Daily* that mixing melamine into animal feed was an "open secret" in the industry: melamine scrap was mixed into an inexpensive "protein powder" resold to feed suppliers.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] People in the trade interviewed by *BusinessWeek* also confirmed it was common practice, and had been going on for "years", with most believing it to be non-toxic to animals.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Melamine dealers said after Sanlu, the government started clamping down on melamine sales to food processing companies or to manufacturers of animal feed.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Malaysian authorities determined that ammonium bicarbonate, not milk, imported from China was the source of contamination at the Khong Guan and Khian Guan biscuit factory.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Malaysian authorities said it was probable cross contamination of batches from Chinese companies Broadtech Chemical Int.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Co Ltd, Dalian Chemical Industries and Tianjin Red Triangle International Trading Co, and did not suspect adulteration.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 19 October, Taiwanese authorities detected melamine in 469 tons of ammonium bicarbonate imported from China.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Samples tested showed up to 2,470ppm of melamine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Public concerns have resulted in demand and egg prices falling throughout the country.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Prices at a large Beijing wholesale market dropped 10%, and prices fell by 10% the day after news of the contamination broke in Hong Kong.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Wholesalers have refused to stock products without melamine inspection certificates.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The *Beijing Youth Daily* reported that farmers had been forced to slaughter tens of thousands of chickens.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The website upset Chinese authorities, who detained Zhao in November 2009 and arrested him in December 2009.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The Chinese government said that producers violating the law "could have their licenses revoked and be handed over to law enforcement organs".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] A senior Agriculture Ministry official said that of a quarter of a million feed-makers and animal farms inspected for melamine contamination, inspectors found more than 500 engaged in "illegal or questionable practices".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Some 3,700 tonnes of feed with excessive melamine were seized.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Local government, for example Guangdong authorities, have increased random inspections at poultry farms.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] They declared to "harshly crack down on the unlawful behaviour of illegally manufacturing, selling and using melamine".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 2 December 2009, China detained three employees of Shaanxi Jinqiao Dairy Company in northwest China suspected of selling 5.25 tons of melamine-laced powdered milk to Nanning Yueqian Food Additive Company, in Guangxi.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 30 December 2009, Xinhua reported continuing problems: powder and flavouring products sold by another company involved in the original scandal–the Shanghai Panda Dairy Company–were found to contain illegal levels of melamine; the dairy was closed and three of its executives arrested.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 25 January 2010, it was reported that three food companies from Hebei, Liaoning and Shandong provinces had produced melamine tainted products in March and April 2009 and that the three companies were banned from selling products in Guizhou.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] On 10 February 2010 China's state council announced a food safety commission, consisting of three vice premiers and a dozen minister-level officials, to address the nation's food regulatory problems.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] The group aims to improve government coordination and enforcement and to solve systemic food safety problems.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] In July 2010, Xinhua reported that authorities had seized 64 tonnes of dairy product contaminated with melamine from Dongyuan Dairy Factory, in Minhe County, in Qinghai, after authorities in Gansu discovered the contaminated powdered milk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Approximately 38 tonnes of raw materials had been purchased from Hebei, raising the possibility that traders had bought tainted milk that was supposed to have been destroyed after the 2008 scandal.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Police have detained the owner and production director of the factory.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Powdered milk produced in the plant was mainly sold in Zhejiang and Jiangsu, with only a small amount sold in Qinghai.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Also, in Jilin, authorities were testing samples of suspect powdered milk produced in Heilongjiang.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] At the end of June 2010, Beijing lowered the minimum protein level for raw milk, from 2.955 to 2.8%, to discourage dairy farmers from attempting to falsify the passing of protein tests.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] Wu Heping, secretary general of the Heilongjiang Dairy Industry Association noted that between 75% and 90% of raw milk in some provinces had failed to reach the old protein level standard (in place since 1986) in 2007 and 2008.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] He said that the new standard reflected "the reality of the domestic dairy farm industry".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2008-chinese-milk-scandal-p02] However, Guangzhou dairy industry association president Wang Dingmian stated that this alone would not remove the incentive for adulteration, because milk price still depends on protein content.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February 2022, during the Russo-Ukrainian war, Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine, starting the current phase of the war, the largest conflict in Europe since World War II.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By April 2022, the invasion's initial goal of a rapid Russian victory via decapitation had failed, with Ukraine pushing back the northern arm of the invasion and preventing the capture of Kyiv.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Following this, the war transitioned to more conventional fighting in the south and east of Ukraine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In a televised address, Russian president Vladimir Putin announced the invasion, calling it a "special military operation".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said that its purpose was to support the Russian-backed breakaway republics of Donetsk and Luhansk, whose paramilitary forces had been fighting Ukraine in the war in Donbas since 2014.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin espoused irredentist and imperialist views challenging Ukraine's legitimacy as a state, baselessly claimed that the Ukrainian government were neo-Nazis committing genocide against the Russian minority in the Donbas, and said that Russia's goal was to "demilitarise and denazify" Ukraine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In late 2021, Russia massed troops near Ukraine's borders and issued demands to the West including a ban on Ukraine ever joining the NATO military alliance.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After repeatedly denying having plans to attack Ukraine, on 24 February 2022, Russian air strikes and a ground invasion were launched on a northern front from Belarus towards the capital Kyiv, a southern front from Crimea, and an eastern front from the Donbas and towards Kharkiv.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine enacted martial law, ordered a general mobilisation, and severed diplomatic relations with Russia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion was met with widespread international condemnation.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The United Nations General Assembly passed a resolution condemning the invasion and demanding a full Russian withdrawal.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Court of Justice ordered Russia to halt military operations, and the Council of Europe expelled Russia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Many countries imposed sanctions on Russia and its ally Belarus and provided humanitarian and military aid to Ukraine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Baltic states and Poland declared Russia a terrorist state.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests occurred around the world, with anti-war protesters in Russia being met by mass arrests and greater media censorship.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into crimes against humanity, war crimes, abduction of Ukrainian children, and genocide against Ukrainians.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The ICC issued arrest warrants for Putin and other Russian officials.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In 2013, Ukraine's parliament overwhelmingly approved finalising an association agreement with the European Union (EU), which had been negotiated for several years.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia put pressure on Ukraine to reject the agreement and imposed economic sanctions on the country.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin adviser Sergei Glazyev warned in September 2013 that if Ukraine signed the EU agreement, Russia would no longer acknowledge Ukraine's borders.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In November, Ukrainian president Viktor Yanukovych suddenly withdrew from signing the agreement, choosing closer ties to the Russian-led Eurasian Economic Union instead.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This coerced withdrawal triggered a wave of protests known as Euromaidan, culminating in the Revolution of Dignity in February 2014.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Despite signing an agreement, Yanukovych fled.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Parliament voted to remove him and he ended up in Russia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian soldiers with no insignia occupied the Ukrainian territory of Crimea, and seized the Crimean Parliament.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia annexed Crimea in March 2014, after a widely disputed referendum held under occupation.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Pro-Russian protests immediately followed in the Ukrainian cities of Donetsk and Luhansk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war in Donbas began in April 2014 when armed Russian mercenaries led by Igor 'Strelkov' Girkin seized Sloviansk and nearby towns.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops were covertly involved in the fighting.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Minsk agreements, signed in September 2014 and February 2015, aimed to resolve the conflict, but ceasefires and further negotiations repeatedly failed.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] There was a large Russian military build-up near Ukraine's borders in March and April 2021, and again in both Russia and Belarus from October 2021 onward.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Members of the Russian government, including Putin, denied having plans to attack or invade Ukraine up until the day before the invasion.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] While Russian troops massed on Ukraine's borders, Russia's proxy forces launched thousands of attacks on Ukrainian forces in the Donbas.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Observers from the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE), which also includes Ukraine and Russia, reported more than 90,000 ceasefire violations throughout 2021; the vast majority in Russian-controlled territory.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In July 2021, Putin published an essay "On the Historical Unity of Russians and Ukrainians", in which he called Ukraine "historically Russian lands" and claimed there is "no historical basis" for the "idea of Ukrainian people as a nation separate from the Russians".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin was accused of promoting Russian imperialism, historical revisionism and disinformation.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024, Michael McFaul and Robert Person described this essay as representing not only "cynical propaganda" but also Putin's "deeply held and internalized beliefs".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In December 2021, Russia issued an ultimatum to the West, which included demands that NATO end all activity in its Eastern European member states and ban Ukraine or any other former Soviet state from ever joining the alliance.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia's government said NATO was a threat and warned of a military response if it followed an "aggressive line".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg replied that "Russia has no veto" on whether Ukraine joins, and "has no right to establish a sphere of influence to try to control their neighbours".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Several Western political analysts suggested Russia knew that its "unrealistic demands" would be rejected, which would give it a pretext to invade.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political scientists Michael McFaul and Robert Person said Russia's occupation of Crimea and the Donbas since 2014 had already blocked Ukraine's NATO membership, suggesting that Putin's real aim was to subjugate Ukraine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO offered to negotiate some of Russia's demands and to improve military transparency, as long as Russia stopped its troop buildup.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The alliance rejected Russia's demand to keep Ukraine out of NATO forever, pointing out that Russia had signed agreements affirming the right of Ukraine and other countries to join alliances.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The US proposed that itself and Russia sign an agreement not to station missiles or troops in Ukraine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin replied that Russia's demands had been "ignored", and the Russian troop buildup continued.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Western leaders vowed that heavy sanctions would be imposed should Putin choose to invade rather than to negotiate.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] French president Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz met Putin in February 2022 to dissuade him from invading.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Scholz, Putin told him that Ukraine should not be an independent state.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Scholz told Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskyy to declare Ukraine a neutral country and renounce its aspirations to join NATO.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said Putin had broken agreements and could not be trusted to respect Ukrainian neutrality.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine had been a neutral country in 2014 when Russia occupied Crimea and invaded the Donbas.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 19 February, Zelenskyy made a speech at the Munich Security Conference, calling for Western powers to end their "appeasement" of Putin and give a timeframe for when Ukraine could join NATO.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political analysts Taras Kuzio and Vladimir Socor agree that "when Russia made its decision to invade Ukraine, that country was more remote than ever not only from NATO membership but from any track that might lead to membership".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting in Donbas escalated from 17 February 2022.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainians and the Russian separatists accused one another of firing into their respective territories.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 February, the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics ordered all civilians to leave their capitals, although observers noted that full evacuations would take months.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian media reported a sharp increase in artillery shelling by the Russian-led militants in Donbas as an attempt to provoke the Ukrainian army.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Separatist leaders warned that Ukraine was about to launch an offensive, but they gave no evidence, and *The Guardian* noted it would be "exceedingly risky" for Ukraine to assault the Donbas while Russian troops were massed on its borders.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said his military would not respond to the provocations.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the days leading up to the invasion, the Russian government intensified its disinformation campaign.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine and Western leaders accused Russia of staging false flag attacks to give Russia a pretext for invading.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian state media aired fabricated videos that purported to show Ukrainian forces attacking Russians in Donbas; evidence showed that the claimed attacks, explosions, and evacuations were staged by Russia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 17 February, Russian proxy forces shelled a kindergarten and blamed it on Ukraine, although the kindetgarten was in Ukrainian-held territory.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, the head of the Russian Federal Security Service (FSB) said that Russian forces had killed five Ukrainian "saboteurs" that crossed into Russian territory, capturing one Ukrainian serviceman and destroying two armoured vehicles.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The claim was denied by Ukraine and drew warnings that Russia was seeking further justification to start an invasion.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, Putin announced that the Russian government would recognise the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, Putin directed that Russian troops be deployed to the Donbas, in what he called a "peacekeeping mission".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the same speech, Putin questioned the validity of the Ukrainian nation, stating that "Modern Ukraine was entirely created by Russia", views which Michael McFaul and Robert Person, writing in 2024, described as "grotesque".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The 21 February intervention in Donbas was condemned by several members of the UN Security Council; none voiced support.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 22 February, video footage shot in the early morning showed Russian armed forces and tanks moving in the Donbas region.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Federation Council unanimously authorised the use of military force outside Russia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Zelenskyy ordered the conscription of army reservists.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The following day, Ukraine's parliament proclaimed a 30-day nationwide state of emergency and ordered the mobilisation of all reservists.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia began to evacuate its embassy in Kyiv.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The websites of the Ukrainian parliament and government, along with banking websites, were hit by DDoS attacks, widely attributed to Russian-backed hackers.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the night of 23 February, Zelenskyy gave a speech in Russian in which he appealed to the citizens of Russia to prevent war.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He also refuted Russia's claims about the presence of neo-Nazis in the Ukrainian government and said that he had no intention of attacking the Donbas region.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov said on 23 February that the separatist leaders in Donetsk and Luhansk had sent a letter to Putin stating that Ukrainian shelling had caused civilian deaths and appealing for Russian military support.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Ukraine requested an urgent UN Security Council meeting.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Half an hour into the emergency meeting, Putin announced the start of military operations in Ukraine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sergiy Kyslytsya, the Ukrainian representative, subsequently called on the Russian representative, Vasily Nebenzya, to "do everything possible to stop the war" or relinquish his position as president of the UN Security Council; Nebenzya refused.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The decision to invade was reportedly made by Putin and a small group of war hawks or *siloviki* in Putin's inner circle, including national security adviser Nikolai Patrushev and defence minister Sergei Shoigu.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the start of the invasion, Ukrainian and Western analysts assessed that Putin seemed to have believed that the Russian Armed Forces would be capable of seizing Kyiv within days.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This assessment led to the conclusion that "taking Kyiv in three days" had been the original goal of the invasion.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The narrative of the planned "three day" capture of Kyiv was reinforced by statements by Aleksandr Lukashenko and Margarita Simonyan, editor-in-chief of Russian state-controlled broadcaster RT.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, the Security Service of Ukraine (SBU) repeated the claim following its release of a video showing a captured Russian soldier claiming that his unit was sent into Ukraine with food supplies for only three days.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Documents found inside Russian tanks mention how the "special military operation" would conclude in ten days.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine also captured "flagship" tanks – as used in parades – along with military parade uniforms, suggesting that Russia expected to stage a victory parade in Kyiv after a swift conquest.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin himself asserted back in 2014 that Russian forces "could take Ukraine in two weeks".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three days after the invasion began, RIA Novosti, a Russian state news agency, mistakenly published an article called "Russia's Coming and the New World", which had been made in advance in anticipation of a Russian victory; it announced that "Ukraine had returned to Russia".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy also said that Russia had sent him an ultimatum to step down and be replaced with Viktor Medvedchuk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time on 24 February, Putin, in another speech, announced a "special military operation", which effectively declared war on Ukraine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said the operation was to "protect the people" of the Russian-controlled breakaway republics.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said Russia sought the "demilitarisation and denazification" of Ukraine, and denied the legitimacy of the Ukrainian state.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said he had no plans to occupy Ukraine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began within minutes of Putin's speech.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In order to justify the invasion of Ukraine within the context of international norms, Putin cited the 1999 NATO bombing of Yugoslavia and 2003 US invasion of Iraq.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion comprised nearly 150,000 troops, organised in about 140 Battalion Tactical Groups.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The forces of the Russia-controlled LNR and DNR, and paramilitary forces engaged in the invasion, raised total Russian-controlled forces employed in the campaign to as many as 200,000.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These forces were organised into groups having tactical signs to distinguish them, and were to advance into Ukraine along at least ten different axes of advance.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Rather than having a unified command-structure, these groups were organised under different Russian military-district command-posts named after the region of Russia in which their respective military-district was located.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three groups, all having the tactical sign "Z" and commanded by the Western Military District under Alexander Zhuravlyov, were to advance into Ukraine respectively from Kursk, Belgorod and Voronezh.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Groups under the Southern Military District under Aleksandr Dvornikov were identified with a "Z in a square" tactical symbol, and, advancing from occupied Crimea, were tasked with surrounding Mariupol, capturing Zaporizhia, seizing Kherson, and crossing the Dnieper river to take Voznesensk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion were equipped with roughly 2,800 tanks ready for combat, with another 400 approximately in the hands of the Russian-controlled proxy forces of the LNR and DNR.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces at the outbreak of the war comprised roughly 20 combat-ready brigades, of which more than half were located in the east of the country, positioned along the line of contact in the "Joint Forces Operation" zone in Donbas.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] An additional manoeuvre brigade and two brigades of artillery were located in the Kyiv region, with other forces also deployed in the area of Kharkiv, Dnipro, Sumy, and Odesa.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] No major combat units were located on the Gomel or Crimean axes.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian tank-forces had roughly 900 battle-ready tanks organised in some 30 battalions at the time of the invasion.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of these tank battalions were formed in the period 2014–2018, when roughly 500 tanks were delivered to the Ukrainian armed forces, mostly reconditioned older tanks rather than new-built tanks, particularly T-64B and T-64-BM tanks.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The tank battalions were spread between Ukraine's two regular and four reserve armoured brigades, as well as tank units attached to brigades of mechanised, mountain, airborne and marine infantry.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In contrast to the direct-fire techniques practised in most armoured forces, Ukrainian forces had, based on their experience during the war in Donbas, developed a technique of using tanks in the indirect-fire role.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This meant Ukrainian tank forces acting essentially as mobile artillery that did not require the kind of screening that traditional artillery units require.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began at dawn on 24 February.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting began in Luhansk Oblast at 3:40 a.m.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time near Milove on the border with Russia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The main infantry and tank attacks were launched in four spearheads, creating a northern front launched towards Kyiv from Belarus, a southern front from Crimea, a southeastern front from Russian-controlled Donbas, and an eastern front from Russia towards Kharkiv and Sumy.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian vehicles were subsequently marked with a white *Z* military symbol (a non-Cyrillic letter), believed to be a measure to prevent friendly fire.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Immediately after the invasion began, Zelenskyy declared martial law in Ukraine in a first video speech.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, he ordered a general mobilisation of all Ukrainian males between 18 and 60 years old, prohibiting them from leaving the country.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wagner Group mercenaries and Kadyrovites contracted by the Kremlin reportedly made several attempts to assassinate Zelenskyy, including an operation involving several hundred mercenaries meant to infiltrate Kyiv with the aim of killing the Ukrainian president.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainian government said anti-war officials within Russia's FSB shared the plans with them.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy appeared defiant in video messages on 24 through 26 February, that he and his cabinet is still in Kyiv.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February NATO met and its countries pledged military aid for Ukraine and on 27 February Germany called the invasion a historic watershed.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] That day in the evening Putin put Russia's nuclear deterrence into alert.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian invasion was unexpectedly met by fierce Ukrainian resistance.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Kyiv, Russia failed to take the city and was repulsed in the battles of Irpin, Hostomel, and Bucha.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians tried to encircle the capital, but its defenders under Oleksandr Syrskyi held their ground, effectively using Western Javelin anti-tank missiles and Stinger anti-aircraft missiles to thin Russian supply lines and stall the offensive.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the southern front, Russian forces had captured the regional capital of Kherson by 2 March.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A column of Russian tanks and armoured vehicles was ambushed on 9 March outside of Brovary and sustained heavy losses that forced them to retreat.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian army adopted siege tactics on the western front around the key cities of Chernihiv, Sumy and Kharkiv, but failed to capture them due to stiff resistance and logistical setbacks.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Mykolaiv Oblast, Russian forces advanced as far as Voznesensk, but were repelled and pushed back south of Mykolaiv.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A second axis, deployed towards eastern Kyiv from Russia by the Central Military District (northeastern front), comprised the 41st Combined Arms Army and the 2nd Guards Combined Arms Army.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third axis was deployed towards Kharkiv by the Western Military District (eastern front), with the 1st Guards Tank Army and 20th Combined Arms Army.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 7 April, Russian troops deployed to the northern front by the Russian Eastern Military District pulled back from the Kyiv offensive, reportedly to resupply and redeploy to the Donbas region in an effort to reinforce the renewed invasion of southeastern Ukraine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The northeastern front, including the Central Military District, was similarly withdrawn for resupply and redeployment to southeastern Ukraine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian efforts to capture Kyiv included a probative spearhead on 24 February, from Belarus south along the west bank of the Dnipro River.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The apparent intent was to encircle the city from the west, supported by two separate axes of attack from Russia along the east bank of the Dnipro: the western at Chernihiv, and from the east at Sumy.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These were likely intended to encircle Kyiv from the northeast and east.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia tried to seize Kyiv quickly, with Spetsnaz infiltrating into the city supported by airborne operations and a rapid mechanised advance from the north, but failed.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reporter Glenn Kessler said it came from "a single source, but on the surface it appears to be a good one".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advancing on Kyiv from Belarus gained control of the ghost town of Chernobyl.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian Airborne Forces attempted to seize two key airfields near Kyiv, launching an airborne assault on Antonov Airport, and a similar landing at Vasylkiv, near Vasylkiv Air Base, on 26 February.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By early March, further Russian advances along the west side of the Dnipro were limited, after suffering setbacks from Ukrainian defence.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As of 5 March, a large Russian convoy, reportedly 64 kilometres (40 mi) in length, had made little progress toward Kyiv.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The London-based think tank Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) assessed the Russian performance from the north and east as "stalled".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Advances along the Chernihiv axis had largely halted as a siege of the city began.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also continued advancing from the northwest of Kyiv, capturing Bucha, Hostomel, and Vorzel by 5 March, though Irpin remained contested as of 9 March.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 11 March, it was reported that the lengthy convoy had largely dispersed, taking up positions that offered tree cover.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 16 March, Ukrainian forces began a counter-offensive to repel Russian forces approaching Kyiv from several surrounding cities.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 20 March, the Russian military appeared to be waging a rapid invasion to achieve its apparent primary goal of the seizure of Kyiv, along with the occupation of Eastern Ukraine and the overthrow of the Ukrainian government.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Unable to achieve a quick victory in Kyiv, Russian forces switched strategies and began using standoff weapons, indiscriminate bombing, and siege warfare.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Ukrainian counteroffensive in Kyiv resulted in several towns, including Makariv, being retaken to the east and west of Kyiv.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As part of a general retreat of Russian forces north of Kyiv, as well as attacks on Russian formations by the Ukrainian military, Russian troops in the Bucha area retreated north by the end of March.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces entered the city on 1 April.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine claimed to recapture the entire region around Kyiv, including Irpin, Bucha, and Hostomel, by 2 April, with evidence of war crimes being uncovered in Bucha.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advanced into Chernihiv Oblast on 24 February, besieging its administrative capital within four days of fighting.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February Ukrainian forces lost control over Konotop.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also attacked Okhtyrka, deploying thermobaric weapons.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 4 March, Frederick Kagan wrote that the Sumy axis was then "the most successful and dangerous Russian avenue of advance on Kyiv", and commented that the geography favoured mechanised advances as the terrain "is flat and sparsely populated, offering few good defensive positions".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Travelling along highways, Russian forces reached Brovary, an eastern suburb of Kyiv, on 4 March.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Pentagon confirmed on 6 April that the Russian army had left Chernihiv Oblast, but Sumy Oblast remained contested.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 7 April, the governor of Sumy Oblast said that Russian troops were gone, but had left behind rigged explosives and other hazards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces took control of the North Crimean Canal, allowing Crimea to obtain water from the Dnieper, which had been cut off since 2014.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February, the siege of Mariupol began as the attack moved east linking to separatist-held Donbas.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] En route, Russian forces entered Berdiansk and captured it.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, Russian units from the DPR were fighting near Pavlopil as they moved on Mariupol.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By evening, the Russian Navy began an amphibious assault on the coast of the Sea of Azov 70 kilometres (43 mi) west of Mariupol.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A US defence official said that Russian forces were deploying thousands of marines from this beachhead.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian 22nd Army Corps approached the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant on 26 February and besieged Enerhodar.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A fire began, but the Ukrainian military said that essential equipment was undamaged.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third Russian attack group from Crimea moved northwest and captured the bridge over the Dnieper.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian troops took Kherson; this was the first major city to fall to Russian forces.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops moved on Mykolaiv and attacked it two days later.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After renewed missile attacks on 14 March in Mariupol, the Ukrainian government said more than 2,500 had died.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 18 March, Mariupol was completely encircled and fighting reached the city centre, hampering efforts to evacuate civilians.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 20 March, an art school sheltering around 400 people, was destroyed by Russian bombs.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians demanded surrender, and the Ukrainians refused.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin told Emmanuel Macron in a phone call on 29 March that the bombardment of Mariupol would only end when the Ukrainians surrendered.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 April, Russian troops refused safe passage into Mariupol to 50 buses sent by the United Nations to evacuate civilians, as peace talks continued in Istanbul.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 3 April, following the retreat of Russian forces from Kyiv, Russia expanded its attack on southern Ukraine further west, with bombardment and strikes against Odesa, Mykolaiv, and the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the east, Russian troops attempted to capture Kharkiv, less than 35 kilometres (22 mi) from the Russian border, and met strong Ukrainian resistance.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces with OTR-21 Tochka missiles, which according to Ukrainian officials, destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and started a fire.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 March, Denis Pushilin, head of the DPR, announced that DPR forces had almost completely surrounded the city of Volnovakha.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian forces were repelled from Sievierodonetsk during an attack against the city.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the same day, Ukrainian forces initiated a counter-offensive on Horlivka, controlled by the DPR.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Izium was captured by Russian forces on 1 April after a monthlong battle.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Russian defence ministry said it would seek to occupy major cities in eastern Ukraine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 31 March, *PBS News* reported renewed shelling and missile attacks in Kharkiv, as bad or worse than before, as peace talks with Russia were to resume in Istanbul.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Amid the heightened Russian shelling of Kharkiv on 31 March, Russia reported a helicopter strike against an oil supply depot approximately 35 kilometres (22 mi) north of the border in Belgorod, and accused Ukraine of the attack.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Local governor Maksym Kozytskyy reported that at least 35 people had been killed in the attacks.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 March, Russia expanded the attack to Lviv, with Ukrainian military officials saying initial information suggested that the missiles which hit Lviv were likely air-launched cruise missiles originating from warplanes flying over the Black Sea.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces attacked the Chuhuiv air base, which housed Bayraktar TB2 drones.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The attack caused damage to fuel storage areas and infrastructure.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The next day, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces using OTR-21 Tochka missiles.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Ukrainian officials, this destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and set the airbase on fire.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the Zhytomyr Airport attack on 27 February, it was reported that Russia used 9K720 Iskander missile systems, located in Belarus, to attack the civilian Zhytomyr Airport.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia lost at least ten aircraft on 5 March.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 6 March, the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Ukraine reported that 88 Russian aircraft had been destroyed since the war began.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, an anonymous senior US defence official told Reuters on 7 March that Russia still had the "vast majority" of its fighter jets and helicopters that had been amassed near Ukraine available to fly.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the first month of the invasion, Justin Bronk, a British military observer, counted the Russian aircraft losses at 15 fixed-wing aircraft and 35 helicopters, but noted that the true total was certainly higher.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 13 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine lies on the Black Sea, which only has access through the Turkish-held Bosphorus and Dardanelles straits.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 28 February, Turkey invoked the 1936 Montreux Convention and sealed off the straits to Russian warships not registered as having Black Sea home bases and not returning to their ports of origin.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This prevented the passage of four Russian naval vessels through the Turkish Straits.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine announced that an attack on Snake Island by Russian Navy ships had begun.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The cruiser *Moskva* and patrol boat *Vasily Bykov* bombarded the island with their deck guns.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] When the Russian warship identified itself and instructed the Ukrainian soldiers stationed on the island to surrender, their response was "Russian warship, go fuck yourself!" After the bombardment, a detachment of Russian soldiers landed and took control of Snake Island.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia stated on 26 February that US drones were supplying intelligence to the Ukrainian navy to help target Russian warships in the Black Sea, which the US denied.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 3 March, the Ukrainian frigate *Hetman Sahaidachny*, the flagship of the Ukrainian navy, was scuttled in Mykolaiv to prevent its capture by Russian forces.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, the Russian source RT reported that the Russian Armed Forces had captured about a dozen Ukrainian ships in Berdiansk, including the *Polnocny*-class landing ship *Yuri Olefirenko*.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 March, Ukrainian officials said that a Russian landing ship docked in Berdiansk was destroyed by a Ukrainian rocket attack.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Military analysts have been highly critical of the Russian plan of invasion.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kofman also criticised the use of "thunder runs" similar to those used by US forces in the 2003 Iraq war, in an environment where resistance to such attempts to go around urban centres was likely to be far higher.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The November 2022 Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) report on the invasion also criticised the invasion plan as being based on "false assumptions", and spreading Russian forces too thinly across too many objectives, with insufficient contingency-planning for what to do if things went wrong.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Nevertheless, RUSI also stated that "If competently executed, these plans could have succeeded".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024 in the *Journal of Strategic Studies*, analysts from the Swiss Military Academy at ETH Zurich characterised the invasion plan as being "predicated on a rapid, decisive overthrow of the government in Kyiv, presuming minimal resistance".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] They also criticised what they saw as the excessively rigid, Soviet-style command structure and operational planning of Russian forces during the invasion.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian air forces during the campaign were described by military analyst Sean M.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser, writing in 2023 in the *Small Wars & Insurgencies* journal, as having "bungled air operations from the outset of the war".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser described the Russian air forces as having "settled largely for a 'tie'" during the period of the invasion.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The force-structure of Russian forces during the invasion has also been criticised, particularly the use of battalion tactical groups (BTGs), which proved brittle once Ukrainian resistance was met.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Whilst praising Ukraine's resistance to the invasion, analysts have also identified deficiencies in the deployment of Ukrainian forces before the invasion.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] At the tactical level, however, RUSI assessed Ukrainian forces as comprising "units which had been psychologically and practically preparing for this fight for eight years".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Alexander Hill described Ukrainian forces as having undergone a transformation since the fighting of 2014, and having become "a stubborn opponent that was typically difficult [for Russian troops] to dislodge".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces did not deploy an overall commander for the invasion of Ukraine, with command divided between the military district commanders, each of whom was assigned to their own axis of attack.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Mason Clark of the Institute for the Study of War, this resulted in commanders competing for central resources and each effectively fighting their own war.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Subsequent to the failure of this strategy, according to Clark, Putin appointed Aleksandr Dvornikov as an overall commander in Ukraine on 8 April 2022, however Dvornikov retained his post as commander of the Southern Military District.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Disatisfied with Dvornikov's performance, according to Clark, Putin then dismissed Dvornikov as overall commander in June 2022 but allowed him to remain in overall command for several weeks, before Gennady Zhidko was reportedly appointed to that role.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, according to Clark, both Zhidko and Dvornikov were effectively "first among equals" among the Russian Military District Commanders rather than true theatre commanders, and it was not until October 2022 that a dedicated theatre commander - Sergey Surovikin - was appointed.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia abandoned the attempt to take Kyiv in early April, but a lasting state of war between Russia and Ukraine remained, with Russia capturing Mariupol by 20 May 2022, and maintaining an occupation of large portions of four Ukrainian oblasts—Donetsk, Kherson, Luhansk, and Zaporizhzhia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In August, Ukrainian forces began liberating territories in the north-east and south.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 30 September 2022, Russia declared the annexation of the four partially-occupied oblasts, which was internationally condemned.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of Luhansk Oblast and part of Donetsk Oblast had been controlled by pro-Russian separatists since 2014, while the Kherson and Zaporizhzhia oblasts were invaded by Russia in 2022.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The boundaries of the areas to be annexed and their borders were not defined; Russian officials stated that they would be defined later.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] None of the oblasts were fully under Russian control at the time of the declaration, nor since.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] If limited to the areas then under Russian control (about 90,000 km2 or 15% of Ukraine's territory, roughly the size of Portugal) the annexation would still be the largest in Europe since World War II.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In other respects as well—in terms of the scale and intensity of hostilities, and the number of casualties—after the invasion, the war became the biggest war in Europe since World War II.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] From then through 2023, Russian offensives and Ukrainian counteroffensives gained only small amounts of territory.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war has also led to attacks in Russia by Ukrainian and Ukrainian-backed forces, among them a cross-border offensive into Russia's Kursk region in August 2024.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia has repeatedly carried out deliberate and indiscriminate attacks on civilians far from the frontline.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into war crimes and issued arrest warrants for Putin and several other Russian officials.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion received widespread international condemnation from governments and intergovernmental organisations.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March 2022 and on 23 February 2023, 141 member states of the UN General Assembly voted for a resolution saying that Russia should immediately withdraw.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Seven, including Russia, voted against the measure.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political reactions to the invasion included new sanctions imposed on Russia, which triggered widespread economic effects on the Russian and world economies.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sanctions forced Russia to reorient its oil exports to non-sanctioning countries such as India, rely more on LNG (which was not subject to European Union sanctions), and shift its coal exports from Europe to Asia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most European countries cancelled nuclear cooperation with Russia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Over seventy sovereign states and the European Union delivered humanitarian aid to Ukraine, and nearly fifty countries plus the EU provided military aid.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Economic sanctions included a ban on Russian aircraft using EU airspace, a ban of certain Russian banks from the SWIFT international payments system, and a ban on certain Russian media outlets.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reactions to the invasion have included public response, media responses, peace efforts, and the examination of the legal implications of the invasion.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Some countries, particularly in the Global South, saw public sympathy or outright support for Russia, due in part to distrust of US foreign policy.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests and demonstrations were held worldwide, including some in Russia and parts of Ukraine occupied by Russia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Calls for a boycott of Russian goods spread on social media platforms, while hackers attacked Russian websites, particularly those operated by the Russian government.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Anti-Russian sentiment against Russians living abroad surged after the invasion.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In March 2022, Russian's parliament introduced prison sentences of up to 15 years for publishing "fake news" about Russian military operations, intended to suppress any criticism related to the war.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/a-place-at-the-table] Participant Media is the entertainment company behind the film, and it is distributed by Magnolia Pictures.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/a-place-at-the-table] The Participant/Magnolia team is also responsible for the film *Food, Inc.* (2008).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/a-place-at-the-table] The film was originally titled *Finding North* but the name was later changed to *A Place at the Table*.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/a-place-at-the-table] As of 2012, about 50 million Americans were food insecure.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/a-place-at-the-table] This was approximately 1 in 6 of the overall population, with the proportion of children facing food insecurity even higher at about 1 in 4.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/a-place-at-the-table] One in every two children receive federal food assistance.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/a-place-at-the-table] Other Americans struggling with hunger are also featured, including a cop whose monthly paychecks only leaves him enough money to buy food for two weeks, forcing him to use a food bank.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/a-place-at-the-table] There is also a companion book titled *A Place at the Table: The Crisis of 49 Million Hungry Americans and How to Solve It,* edited by Peter Pringle and published by Public Affairs.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/a-place-at-the-table] The book features contributions from Jeff Bridges, Ken Cook, Marion Nestle, Bill Shore, Joel Berg, Robert Egger, Janet Poppendieck, David Beckmann, Mariana Chilton, Tom Colicchio, Jennifer Harris, Andy Fisher, Kelly Meyer and directors Kristi Jacobson and Lori Silverbush.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/a-place-at-the-table] The film was nominated for Grand Jury Prize at the 2012 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/a-place-at-the-table] At the 2013 IDA Documentary Awards, the film received the Pare Lorentz Award, which recognizes films for model filmmaking while focusing on the use of the natural environment, and justice for all and the illumination of pressing social problems.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/a-place-at-the-table] As of October 2015, it has a 90% approval ratings from 61 professional reviews aggregated by Rotten Tomatoes.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/abuelita] Abuelita is now produced and sold in chocolate tablets, syrup, or individual packets of powdered mix.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/abuelita] The Abuelita product ingredients (in order of percentage): sugar, chocolate processed with alkali, soy lecithin, vegetable oils (palm, shea nut and/or illipe nut), artificial cinnamon flavor, PGPR (an emulsifier).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/abuelita] The Abuelita Hot Chocolate has been a Mexican staple product since 1939 and can be identified by its unique taste and packaging.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/abuelita] One suggested method for preparing Abuelita is to bring a saucepan of milk (not water) to a boil, then add the tablet of chocolate and stir continuously with a whisk or *molinillo* (a whisk-like wooden stirring spoon native to Meso America).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/abuelita] This action is done until it has reached a melted and bubbly or creamy consistency.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/abuelita] The drink is served hot or chilled to mix with alcoholic beverages.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/abuelita] Abuelita is often prepared for special occasions, such as Day of the Dead (a holiday in which people remember their family and friends whose spirits departed to the afterlife) and Las Posadas (Christmas season).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The **Academy Awards**, more commonly known as the **Oscars**, are awards based on artistic and technical merit in film.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] They are presented annually by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS) in the United States in recognition of excellence in cinematic achievements, as assessed by the Academy's voting membership.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Oscars are widely considered to be the most prestigious awards in the American film industry, predominantly centered around films produced in Hollywood.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The major award categories, known as the **Academy Awards of Merit**, are presented during a live televised Hollywood ceremony in February or March.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] It is the longest running worldwide entertainment awards ceremony.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The 1st Academy Awards were held in 1929.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The second ceremony, in 1930, was the first to be broadcast by radio, and the 1953 ceremony was the first to be televised.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] It is the oldest of the four major annual American entertainment awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Its counterparts — the Emmy Awards for television, the Tony Awards for Broadway theatre, and the Grammy Awards for music — are modeled after the Academy Awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Oscar statuette depicts a knight, rendered in the Art Deco style.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The first Academy Awards presentation was held on May 16, 1929 at a private dinner function at the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel, with an audience of about 270 people.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The post-awards party was held at the Mayfair Hotel.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The cost of guest tickets for that night's ceremony was $5 (equivalent to $94 in 2025).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Fifteen statuettes were awarded, honoring artists, directors, and other participants in the film-making industry of the time, for their works during the 1927–28 period.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] For this first ceremony, winners were announced to the media three months earlier.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] For the second ceremony in 1930, and the rest of the first decade, the results were given to newspapers for publication at 11:00 pm on the night of the awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 1940, the *Los Angeles Times* announced the winners before the ceremony began.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] As a result, in 1941 the Academy started using a sealed envelope to reveal the names of the winners.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The term "Oscar" is a registered trademark of the AMPAS.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Historically, the Oscars had been the prime example of glamor in the United States; however, a movement away from both network television and award shows has led to the shift of the focus of glamor from the Oscars to the Met Gala.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Oscars have suffered declining network television ratings and will be moving to YouTube in 2029.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The first Best Actor awarded was Emil Jannings, for his performances in *The Last Command* and *The Way of All Flesh*.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] As he had to return to Europe before the ceremony, the Academy agreed to give him the prize early, making him the first Academy Award recipient.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] For the first Awards, winners were recognized for multiple films during the qualifying period; Jannings received the award for two films in which he starred, and Janet Gaynor won the first Best Actress award for performances in three films.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Beginning with the second ceremony, performers received separate nominations for individual films; no performer has received multiple nominations in the same category since the 3rd Academy Awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] For the first five ceremonies, the eligibility period ran from August 1 to July 31.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Best Foreign Language Film, now known as Best International Feature Film, was introduced at the 20th Academy Awards as a special award, and became a competitive category at the 29th Academy Awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The 74th Academy Awards, held in 2002, presented the first Academy Award for Best Animated Feature, won by *Shrek*.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Since 1973, all Academy Awards ceremonies, except for 2021, have ended with the Academy Award for Best Picture.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Traditionally, the winners of the acting categories will present an award at the following year's ceremony.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The previous year's winners for Best Actor and Best Supporting Actor present the awards for Best Actress and Best Supporting Actress, respectively, and vice versa.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2009, this model was replaced by each acting award being introduced by five previous winners, each of whom introduces one of the nominated performances, referred to as the "Fab 5" presenters format.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Fab 5 model returned in 2024 after a 15-year hiatus.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] On February 9, 2020, *Parasite* became the first foreign-language film to win Best Picture at the 92nd Academy Awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The 93rd Academy Awards ceremony, honoring the best films of 2020 and early 2021, was held on April 25, 2021, after it was postponed from its original February 28, 2021, schedule due to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on cinema.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] As with the two previous ceremonies, there was no host.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] It took place at the Dolby Theatre in Los Angeles, California for the 19th consecutive year, with satellite locations at Union Station also in Los Angeles.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Because of the virus impact on films and TV industries, Academy president David Rubin and CEO Dawn Hudson announced that for the 2021 Oscar Ceremony, streaming films with a previously planned theatrical release were eligible.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The theatrical requirement was reinstated starting with the 95th Academy Awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Oscar statuette, officially the Academy Award of Merit, is given to winners of each year's awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Made of gold-plated bronze on a black metal base, it is 13.5 in (34.3 cm) tall, weighs 8.5 lb (3.9 kg) and depicts a knight rendered in Art Deco style holding a sword standing on a reel of film with five spokes.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The five spokes represent the original branches of the Academy: Actors, Writers, Directors, Producers, and Technicians.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Sculptor George Stanley, who also did the Muse Fountain at the Hollywood Bowl, sculpted Cedric Gibbons' design.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The statuettes presented at the initial ceremonies were gold-plated solid bronze.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Within a few years, the bronze was abandoned in favor of Britannia metal, a pewter-like alloy that is then plated in copper, nickel silver, and finally, 24-karat gold.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Due to a metal shortage during World War II, Oscars were made of painted plaster for three years.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Following the war, the Academy invited recipients to redeem the plaster figures for gold-plated metal ones.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The only addition to the Oscar since it was created is a minor streamlining of the base.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The original Oscar mold was cast in 1928 at the C.W.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Shumway & Sons Foundry in Batavia, Illinois, which also contributed to casting the molds for the Vince Lombardi Trophy and Emmy Award statuettes.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] From 1972 to 1986, the Oscar statues were cast at the Dodge Trophy Company in Crystal Lake, Illinois.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] From 1987 to 2015, approximately 50 Oscars in a tin alloy with gold plating were made each year in Chicago by Illinois manufacturer R.S.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] It would take between three and four weeks to manufacture 50 statuettes.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2016, the Academy returned to bronze as the core metal of the statuettes, handing manufacturing duties to Walden, New York-based Polich Tallix Fine Art Foundry, now owned and operated by UAP Urban Art Projects.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] While based on a digital scan of an original 1929 Oscar, the statuettes retain their modern-era dimensions and black pedestal.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Cast in liquid bronze from 3D-printed ceramic molds and polished, they are then electroplated in 24-karat gold by Brooklyn, New York-based Epner Technology.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The time required to produce 50 such statuettes is roughly three months.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Owens is expected to continue producing other awards for the Academy, and service existing Oscars that need replating.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The origin of the nickname of the trophy has been disputed, as multiple people have taken credit for naming the trophy "Oscar".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Margaret Herrick, librarian and president of the Academy, may have said she named it after her supposed uncle Oscar in 1931.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The only corroboration was a 1938 clipping from the *Los Angeles Examiner*, in which Herrick told a story of her and her husband joking with each other using the phrase, "How's your uncle Oscar".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Bette Davis, in her 1962 autobiography, claimed she named it in 1936 after her first husband, Harmon Oscar Nelson, of whom the statue's rear end reminded her.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] But the term had been in use at least two years before.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] But in the newspaper clipping that Skolsky referred to, he wrote that "these statues are called 'Oscars'", meaning that the name was already in use.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2021, Brazilian researcher Waldemar Dalenogare Neto contradicted Skolsky's claim to have used the term first, finding the probable first public mention of the name "Oscar" in journalist Relman Morin's "Cinematters" column in the *Los Angeles Evening Record* on December 5, 1933.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Since the awards did not take place that year, he said: "What's happened to the annual Academy banquet?
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Bruce Davis, a former executive director of the Academy, credited Eleanore Lilleberg, a secretary at the Academy when the award was first introduced, for the nickname.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] She had overseen the pre-ceremony handling of the awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Davis credits Lilleberg because he found in an autobiography of Einar Lilleberg, Eleanore's brother, that Einar had referenced a Norwegian army veteran named Oscar whom the two knew in Chicago, whom Einar described as having always "stood straight and tall".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] He asserts credit "should almost certainly belong to" Lilleberg.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] To prevent information identifying the Oscar winners from leaking ahead of the ceremony, Oscar statuettes presented at the ceremony have blank baseplates.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Until 2010, winners returned their statuettes to the Academy and had to wait several weeks to have their names inscribed on their respective Oscars.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Since 2010, winners have had the option of having engraved nameplates applied to their statuettes at an inscription-processing station at the Governor's Ball, a party held immediately after the Oscar ceremony.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Owens company has engraved nameplates made before the ceremony, bearing the name of every potential winner.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The nameplates for the non-winning nominees are later recycled.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Before 1950, Oscar statuettes were, and remain, the property of the recipient.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Since then the statuettes have been legally encumbered by the requirement that the statuette be first offered for sale back to the Academy for $1.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] If a winner refuses to agree to this stipulation, then the Academy keeps the statuette.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Academy Awards predating this agreement have been sold in public auctions and private deals for six-figure sums.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 1989, Michael Todd's grandson tried to sell Todd's Best Picture Oscar for his 1956 production of *Around the World in 80 Days* to a movie prop collector.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Academy earned enforcement of its statuette contract by gaining a permanent injunction against the sale.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 1992, Harold Russell consigned his 1946 Oscar for Best Supporting Actor for *The Best Years of Our Lives* to auction to raise money for his wife's medical expenses.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Though his decision caused controversy, the first Oscar ever to be sold passed to a private collector on August 6, 1992, for $60,500 (equivalent to $138,804 in 2025).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Russell defended his action, saying, "I don't know why anybody would be critical.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] My wife's health is much more important than sentimental reasons.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The movie will be here, even if Oscar isn't".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In December 2011, Orson Welles' 1941 Oscar for *Citizen Kane* (Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay) was put up for auction, after his heirs won a 2004 court decision contending that Welles did not sign any agreement to return the statue to the Academy.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Some buyers have subsequently returned the statuettes to the Academy, which keeps them in its treasury.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Academy also awards Nicholl Fellowships in Screenwriting.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] From 2004 to 2020, the Academy Award nomination results were announced to the public in mid-January.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Prior to that, the results were announced in early February.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2021, the nominees were announced in March.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2022, the nominees were announced in early February for the first time since 2003.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS), a professional honorary organization, is composed of 9,905 voting members as of 2024.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Academy membership is divided into different branches, with each representing a different discipline in film production.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] As of 2024, actors constitute the largest bloc, numbering 1,258 (12.7% of the voting body).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Votes have been certified by the auditing firm PricewaterhouseCoopers, and its predecessor Price Waterhouse, since the 7th Academy Awards in 1935.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In May 2011, the Academy sent a letter advising its then-6,000 or so voting members that an online system for Oscar voting would be implemented in 2013, replacing mailed paper ballots.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] All AMPAS members must be invited to join by the Board of Governors, on behalf of Academy Branch Executive Committees.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Membership eligibility may be achieved by a competitive nomination, or an existing member may submit a name, based on other significant contributions to the field of motion pictures.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] New membership proposals are considered annually.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Academy does not publicly disclose its membership, although as recently as 2007 press releases have announced the names of those who have been invited to join.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2012, the results of a study conducted by the *Los Angeles Times* were published describing the demographic breakdown of approximately 88% of AMPAS' voting membership.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Of the 5,100+ active voters confirmed, 94% were Caucasian, 77% were male, and 54% were found to be over the age of 60.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Thirty-three percent of voting members are former nominees (14%) and winners (19%).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2016, the Academy launched an initiative to expand its membership and increase diversity.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2024, voting membership stood at 9,905.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2025, a newly announced procedure required Academy members to view all nominated films within a category to be eligible to cast a vote in the final round of that category.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The verification process will be done through the Academy's members-only streaming platform and submitting a form for films viewed at in-person events such as at festivals, screenings or private events.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The film must be shown at least three times on each day of its qualifying run, with at least one of the daily showings starting between 6 pm and 10 pm local time.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] For example, the 2009 Best Picture winner, *The Hurt Locker*, was originally first released in 2008, but did not qualify for the 2008 awards, as it did not play its Oscar-qualifying run in Los Angeles until mid-2009, thus qualifying for the 2009 awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Foreign films must include English subtitles.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Each country can submit only one film for consideration in the International Feature Film category per year.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Rule 2 states that a film must be feature-length, defined as a minimum of 40 minutes, except for short-subject awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] It must exist either on a 35 mm or 70 mm film print, or in 24 frame/s or 48 frame/s progressive scan digital cinema format, with a minimum projector resolution of 2,048 by 1,080 pixels.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Since the 90th Academy Awards, presented in 2018, multi-part and limited series have been ineligible for the Best Documentary Feature award.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] This followed the win of *O.J.: Made in America*, an eight-hour presentation that was screened in a limited release before being broadcast in five parts on ABC and ESPN, in that category in 2017.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Academy's announcement of the new rule made no direct mention of that film.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Best International Feature Film award does not require a U.S. release.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] It requires the film to be submitted as its country's official selection.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The qualifying theatrical runs must meet the same requirements as those for non-documentary films regarding numbers and times of screenings.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] A film must have been reviewed by a critic from *The New York Times*, *Time Out New York*, the *Los Angeles Times*, or *LA Weekly*.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Producers must submit an Official Screen Credits online form before the deadline.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] If it is not submitted by the defined deadline, the film will be ineligible for Academy Awards in any year.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The form includes the production credits for all related categories.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Awards in short film categories (Best Documentary Short Subject, Best Animated Short Film, and Best Live Action Short Film) have different eligibility rules from most other competitive awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] First, the qualifying period for release does not coincide with a calendar year, instead covering one year starting on October 1, and ending on September 30 of the calendar year before the ceremony.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Second, there are multiple methods of qualification.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The main method is a week-long theatrical release in *either* New York City *or* Los Angeles County during the eligibility period.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Films can also qualify by winning specified awards at one of several competitive film festivals designated by the Academy, also without regard to prior public distribution.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] A film that is selected as a gold, silver, or bronze medal winner in an appropriate category of the immediately previous Student Academy Awards is also eligible (Documentary category for that award, and Animation, Narrative, Alternative, or International for the other awards).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The requirements for the qualifying theatrical run are also different from those for other awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] For the Documentary award, the screening must start between noon and 10 pm local time.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] For other awards, no specific start time is required, but the film must appear in regular theater listings with dates and screening times.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In late December, ballots and lists of eligible films are sent to the membership.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] For most categories, members from each of the branches vote to determine the nominees only in their respective categories, i.e. only directors vote for directors, writers for writers, actors for actors, etc.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In the special case of Best Picture, all voting members are eligible to select the nominees.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] A number of branches are only eligible to vote in Best Picture during nomination voting; this includes a producers' branch, as Best Picture is awarded to a film's producer(s), and other branches which have no corresponding award.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In all major categories, a variant of the single transferable vote is used, with each member casting a ballot with up to five nominees (ten for Best Picture) ranked preferentially.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In certain categories, including International Feature Film, Documentary and Animated Feature, nominees are selected by special screening committees made up of members from all branches.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In most categories, the winner is selected from among the nominees by plurality voting of all members.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Since 2009, the Best Picture winner has been chosen by instant-runoff voting.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Since 2013, re-weighted range voting has been used to select the nominees for the Best Visual Effects.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Film companies will spend as much as several million dollars on marketing to awards voters for a film in the running for Best Picture, in attempts to improve chances of receiving Oscars and other film awards conferred in Oscar season.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Academy enforces rules to limit overt campaigning by its members to try to eliminate excesses and prevent the process from becoming undignified.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] It has an awards czar on staff who advises members on allowed practices and levies penalties on offenders.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] For example, a producer of the 2009 Best Picture nominee *The Hurt Locker* was disqualified as a producer in the category when he contacted associates urging them to vote for his film and not another that was seen as the front-runner.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] For the 99th Academy Awards (2027) and thereafter, AMPAS announced on May 1, 2026, its planned rules of eligibility.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Actors and scripts generated by artificial intelligence (AI) will be excluded from acting and screenwriting categories, but human actors rendered by AI will be reviewed at discretion.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Another rule change will expand eligibility of international films by allowing films that won eligible qualifying awards at film festivals, like the Palme d'Or (Cannes), the Golden Lion (Venice), and the Platform Prize (Toronto).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Another new rule will allow an actor to be nominated more than once in a same acting category of the year.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Another rule change will clarify eligibility of the Best Original Song category: to be eligible, a first song played as the "first music cue" of the end credits must be heard in at least the film's last fifteen seconds until the end credits start.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Academy Screening Room or Academy Digital Screening Room is a secure streaming platform which allows voting members of the Academy to view all eligible films in one place.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] It was introduced in 2019, for the 2020 Oscars.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] DVD screeners and Academy in-person screenings were still provided.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] For films to be included on the platform, the North American distributor must pay $12,500, including a watermarking fee, and a digital copy of the film to be prepared for streaming by the Academy.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The platform can be accessed via Apple TV and Roku players.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The watermarking process involved several video security firms, creating a forensic watermark and restricting the ability to take screenshots or screen recordings.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2021, for the 2022 Oscars, the Academy banned all physical screeners and in-person screenings, restricting official membership viewing to the Academy Screening Room.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Films eligible in the Documentary and International categories were made available in different sections of the platform.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Distributors can also pay an extra fee to add video featurettes to promote their films on the platform.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The in-person screenings were cancelled because of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Eligible films do not have to be added to the platform, but the Academy advertises them to voting members when they are.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The major awards are presented at a live televised ceremony, commonly in late February or early March following the relevant calendar year, and six weeks after the announcement of the nominees.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] It is the culmination of the film awards season, which usually begins during November or December of the previous year.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] This is an elaborate extravaganza, with the invited guests walking up the red carpet in the creations of the most prominent fashion designers of the day.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Black tie dress is the most common outfit for men.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Fashion may dictate not wearing a bow tie, and musical performers are sometimes not required to adhere to this.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The artists who recorded the nominees for Best Original Song quite often perform those songs live at the awards ceremony, and the fact that they are performing is often used to promote the television broadcast.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Academy Awards is the world's longest-running awards show televised live from the United States to all time zones in North America and worldwide, and gathers millions of viewers elsewhere throughout the world.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Oscars were first televised in 1953 by NBC, which continued to broadcast the event until 1960, when ABC took over, televising the festivities, including the first color broadcast of the event in 1966, to 1970.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] NBC regained the rights for five years (1971–75), then ABC resumed broadcast duties in 1976 and its current contract with the Academy runs through 2028, after which the ceremony will be broadcast exclusively on YouTube starting with 2029's ceremony.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Academy has produced condensed versions of the ceremony for broadcast in international markets, especially those outside of the Americas, in more desirable local timeslots.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The ceremony was broadcast live internationally for the first time via satellite since 1970, but only two South American countries, Chile and Brazil, purchased the rights to air the broadcast.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] By that time, the television rights to the Academy Awards had been sold in 50 countries.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 1980, the rights were sold to 60 countries, and by 1984, the television rights to the Academy Awards were licensed in 76 countries.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2004, the ceremonies were moved up from late March/early April to late February, to help disrupt and shorten the intense lobbying and ad campaigns associated with Oscar season in the film industry.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Another reason was because of the growing television ratings success coinciding with the NCAA division I men's basketball tournament, which would cut into the Academy Awards audience.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 1976 and 1977, ABC's regained Oscars were moved from Tuesday to Monday and went directly opposite the national championship game on NBC.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The earlier date is also to the advantage of ABC, as it now usually occurs during the highly profitable and important February sweeps period.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Some years, the ceremony is moved into the first Sunday of March to avoid a clash with the Winter Olympics.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Another reason for the move to late February and early March is to avoid the awards ceremony occurring so close to the religious holidays of Passover and Easter, which for decades had been a grievance from members and the general public.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Advertising is somewhat restricted, as traditionally no film studios or competitors of official Academy Award sponsors may advertise during the telecast.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] As of 2020, the production of the Academy Awards telecast held the distinction of winning one the highest number of Emmys in history, with 54 wins and 280 nominations overall.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] After many years of being held on Mondays at 6:00 p.m.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Eastern, since the 1999 ceremony, it was moved to Sundays at 5:30 p.m.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The reasons given for the move were that more viewers would tune in on Sundays, that Los Angeles rush-hour traffic jams could be avoided, and an earlier start time would prevent the ceremony from going late into the night in the East.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] For many years the film industry opposed a Sunday broadcast because it would cut into the weekend box office.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2010, the Academy contemplated moving the ceremony even further back into January, citing television viewers' fatigue with the film industry's long awards season.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] However, such an accelerated schedule would dramatically decrease the voting period for its members, to the point where some voters would only have time to view the contending films streamed on their computers, as opposed to traditionally receiving the films and ballots in the mail.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Additionally, a January ceremony on Sunday would clash with National Football League (NFL) playoff games.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2018, the Academy announced that the ceremony would be moved from late February to mid-February beginning with the 92nd Academy Awards in 2020.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2024, the ceremony was moved to an even earlier start time of 4:00 p.m.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] ET, in an effort to improve East Coast viewership by having it conclude within primetime hours.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The change also gave the ability for ABC to air a half-hour of primetime programming as a lead-out program at 7:30 p.m.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] ET, after having sometimes done so in the late-night block following late local newscasts.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Originally scheduled for April 8, 1968, the 40th Academy Awards ceremony was postponed for two days, because of the assassination of Dr.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] On March 30, 1981, the 53rd Academy Awards was postponed for one day, after the attempted assassination of President Ronald Reagan and others in Washington, D.C.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 1993, an *In Memoriam* segment was introduced, honoring those who had made a significant contribution to cinema who had died in the preceding 12 months, a selection compiled by a small committee of Academy members.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] This segment has drawn criticism over the years for the omission of some names.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Criticism was also levied for many years regarding another aspect, with the segment having a "popularity contest" feel as the audience varied their applause to those who had died by the subject's cultural impact.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The applause has since been muted during the telecast, and the audience is discouraged from clapping during the segment and giving silent reflection instead.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] This segment was later followed by a commercial break.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In terms of broadcast length, the ceremony generally averages three and a half hours.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The first Oscars, in 1929, lasted 15 minutes.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] At the other end of the spectrum, the 2002 ceremony lasted four hours and twenty-three minutes.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2010, the organizers of the Academy Awards announced winners' acceptance speeches must not run past 45 seconds.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] This, according to organizer Bill Mechanic, was to ensure the elimination of what he termed "the single most hated thing on the show"—overly long and embarrassing displays of emotion.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2016, in a further effort to streamline speeches, winners' dedications were displayed on an on-screen ticker.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] During the 2018 ceremony, host Jimmy Kimmel acknowledged how long the ceremony had become, by announcing that he would give a brand-new jet ski to whoever gave the shortest speech of the night, a reward won by Mark Bridges when accepting his Best Costume Design award for *Phantom Thread*.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Although still dominant in ratings, the viewership of the Academy Awards has steadily dropped.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The 88th Academy Awards were the lowest-rated in the past eight years (although with increases in male and 18–49 viewership), while the show itself also faced mixed reception.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Following the show, *Variety* reported that ABC was, in negotiating an extension to its contract to broadcast the Oscars, seeking to have more creative control over the broadcast itself.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Currently and nominally, AMPAS is responsible for most aspects of the telecast, including the choice of production staff and hosting, although ABC is allowed to have some input on their decisions.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In August 2016, AMPAS extended its contract with ABC to 2028: the contract neither contains any notable changes nor gives ABC any further creative control over the telecast.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] On December 17, 2025, the Academy announced that YouTube had acquired the rights to the Academy Awards beginning with the 101st ceremony in 2029, replacing ABC under a contract that will last through 2033.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] YouTube will serve as the exclusive worldwide broadcaster of the ceremony, while the Oscars' YouTube channel will also feature other AMPAS-produced ancillary content and events (including ceremonies, interviews, and other digital content).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Academy will also partner with the Google Arts & Culture program to help digitize portions of the Academy Museum of Motion Pictures and the organization's collection.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Historically, the telecast's viewership is higher when box-office hits are favored to win the Best Picture award.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] More than 57.25 million viewers tuned to the telecast for the 70th Academy Awards in 1998, the year of *Titanic*, which generated a box office haul during its initial 1997–98 run of $600.8 million in the US, a box-office record that would remain unsurpassed for years.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The 76th Academy Awards ceremony, in which *The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King* (pre-telecast box office earnings of $368 million) received 11 Awards, including Best Picture, drew 43.56 million viewers.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The most-watched ceremony based on Nielsen ratings to date, was the 42nd Academy Awards (Best Picture *Midnight Cowboy*), which drew a 43.4% household rating on April 7, 1970.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Hoping to reinvigorate the pre-show and ratings, the 2023 Oscars organizers hired members of the Met Gala creative team.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] By contrast, ceremonies honoring films that have not performed well at the box office tend to show weaker ratings, despite how much critical acclaim those films have received.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The 78th Academy Awards, which awarded a low-budget independent film (*Crash* with a pre-Oscar gross of $53.4 million) generated an audience of 38.64 million with a household rating of 22.91%.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2008, the 80th Academy Awards telecast was watched by 31.76 million viewers on average with an 18.66% household rating, the lowest-rated and least-watched ceremony at the time, in spite of celebrating 80 years of the Academy Awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Best Picture winner of that particular ceremony was another independent film (this time, the Coen brothers's *No Country for Old Men*).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Whereas the 92nd Academy Awards drew an average of 23.6 million viewers, the 93rd Academy Awards drew an even lower viewership of 10.4 million, the lowest viewership recorded by Nielsen since it started recording audience totals in 1974.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The 94th and 95th editions drew 16.6 and 18.7 million viewers, respectively, still below the audience of the 92nd edition.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Academy Film Archive holds copies of every Academy Awards ceremony since the 1949 Oscars, as well as material on many prior ceremonies, along with ancillary material related to more recent shows.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Copies are held in a variety of film, video and digital formats.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 1929, the first Academy Awards were presented at a banquet dinner at the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] From 1930 to 1943, the ceremony alternated between two venues: the Ambassador Hotel on Wilshire Boulevard and the Biltmore Hotel in downtown Los Angeles.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Grauman's Chinese Theatre in Hollywood then hosted the awards from 1944 to 1946, followed by the Shrine Auditorium in Los Angeles from 1947 to 1948.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The 21st Academy Awards in 1949 were held at the Academy Award Theatre at what had been the Academy's headquarters on Melrose Avenue in Hollywood.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] From 1950 to 1960, the awards were presented at Hollywood's Pantages Theatre.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] With the advent of television, the awards from 1953 to 1957 took place simultaneously in Hollywood and New York, first at the NBC International Theatre (1953) and the Center Theater (1954), then at the NBC Century Theatre, after which the ceremony took place solely in Los Angeles.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 1961, the Oscars moved to the Santa Monica Civic Auditorium in Santa Monica, California.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 1969, the Academy moved the ceremonies back to Downtown Los Angeles, to the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion at the Los Angeles County Music Center.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In the late 1990s and early 2000s, the ceremony returned to the Shrine Auditorium.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In 2002, Hollywood's Dolby Theatre, previously known as the Kodak Theatre, became the presentation's current venue.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In March 2026, it was announced that the ceremony would relocate to the Peacock Theater beginning in 2029, under a ten-year deal with the venue.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In the first year of the awards, the Best Directing award was split into two categories, Drama and Comedy.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] At times, the Best Original Score award has also been split into separate categories, Drama and Comedy/Musical.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] From the 1930s to the 1960s, the Art Direction (now Production Design), Cinematography, and Costume Design awards were split into two categories (black-and-white films and color films).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Prior to 2012, the Production Design award was called Art Direction, while the Makeup and Hairstyling award was called Makeup.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Prior to 2020, the International Feature Film award was called Foreign Language Film.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In August 2018, the Academy announced that several categories would not be televised live, but recorded during commercial breaks and aired later in the ceremony.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] Following dissent from Academy members, they announced that they would air all 24 categories live.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] This followed several proposals, among them, the introduction of a Popular Film category, that the Academy had announced but did not implement.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In February 2024, the Academy announced it would introduce an award for Achievement in Casting from the 98th ceremony in 2026, having rejected the category in 1999.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] In April 2025, it announced that Best Stunt Design would be introduced from the 100th ceremony in 2028, having rejected the proposal for a Best Stunt Coordination award every year from 1991 to 2012.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] The Special Academy Awards are voted on by special committees, rather than by the Academy membership as a whole.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p01] They are not always presented on an annual basis.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Due to the positive exposure and prestige of the Academy Awards, many studios spend around 25 million dollars and hire publicists specifically to promote their films during what is typically called the "Oscar season".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] This has generated accusations of the Academy Awards being influenced more by marketing and lobbying than by quality.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] William Friedkin, an Academy Award-winning film director and former producer of the ceremony, expressed this sentiment at a conference in New York in 2009, describing it as "the greatest promotion scheme that any industry ever devised for itself".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] A recent technique that has been claimed to be used during the Oscar season is the whisper campaign.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] These campaigns are intended to spread negative perceptions of other films nominated and are believed to be perpetrated by those who were involved in creating the film.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Examples of whisper campaigns include the allegations against *Zero Dark Thirty* suggesting that it justifies torture and the claim that *Lincoln* distorts history.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] This technique was widely used by former producer Harvey Weinstein and his company Miramax, with the campaign strategy gaining further attention after Miramax's *Shakespeare in Love* defeated rival film *Saving Private Ryan* for Best Picture.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] The Oscars have been infamously known for selecting specific genres of films to be awarded.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] The term "Oscar bait" was coined to describe such films.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] This has led, at times, to more specific criticisms that the Academy is disconnected from the audience, e.g., by favoring "Oscar bait" over audience favorites or favoring historical melodramas over critically acclaimed films that depict current life issues.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Despite the success of *The Dark Knight* and *WALL-E*, these films did not receive a Best Picture nomination at the 81st Academy Awards.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] These decisions received substantial criticism and were described as "snubs" by many publications.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] The backlash to the decision was such that, for the 82nd Academy Awards in 2010, the Academy increased the limit for Best Picture nominees from five to ten.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] The Academy Awards have long received criticism over their lack of diversity among the nominees.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] This criticism is based on the statistics from every Academy Awards since 1929, which show that only 6.4% of Academy Award nominees have been non-white and since 1991, 11.2% of nominees have been non-white, with the rate of winners being even more polarizing.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] For a variety of reasons, including marketability and historical bans on interracial couples, a number of high-profile Oscars have been given to yellowface portrayals, as well as performances of Asian characters rewritten for white characters.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] It took until 2023 for an Asian woman to win an Academy Award for Best Actress, when Michelle Yeoh received the award for her performance in *Everything Everywhere All at Once*.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] The 88th awards ceremony became the target of a boycott, popularized on social media with the hashtag #OscarsSoWhite, based on activists' perception that its all-white acting nominee list reflected bias.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] In response, the Academy initiated "historic" changes in membership by 2020.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Some media critics claim the Academy's efforts to address its purported racial, gender and national biases are merely distractions.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] By contrast, the Golden Globe Awards already have multiple winners of Asian descent in leading actress categories.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Some question whether the Academy's definition of "merit" is just or empowering for non-Americans.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] The Academy's Representation and Inclusion Standards have been criticized for excluding Jews as a distinct underrepresented class.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] The Academy has no rules for how to categorize whether a performance is leading or supporting, and it is up to the discretion of the studios whether a given performance is submitted for either Best Actor/Actress or Best Supporting Actor/Actress.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] This has led to situations where a film has two or more co-leads, and one of these is submitted in a supporting category to avoid the two leads competing against each other, and to increase the film's chances of winning.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] This practice has been derisively called "category fraud".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] For example, Rooney Mara was nominated for Best Supporting Actress for *Carol* (2015), despite her having a comparable amount of screentime to Cate Blanchett, who was nominated for Best Actress.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Another example is *Once Upon a Time in Hollywood* (2019), where Brad Pitt was nominated for and won Best Supporting Actor, even though he played an equally important role to Best Actor nominee Leonardo DiCaprio.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] In both these cases, critics argued that the studios behind the films had placed someone who was actually a leading actor or actress into the supporting categories to avoid them competing against their co-lead.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Following its April 2019 board meeting, the Academy Board of Governors agreed to retain the current rules that allow for streaming media films to be eligible for Oscars as long as they have had limited theatrical runs.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] During the 94th Academy Awards on March 27, 2022, Chris Rock joked about Jada Pinkett Smith's shaved head with a *G.I.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Will Smith walked onstage and slapped Rock across the face, then returned to his seat and told Rock, twice, to "Keep my wife's name out [of] your fucking mouth!" While later accepting the Best Actor award for *King Richard*, Smith apologized to the Academy and the other nominees, but not to Rock.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Rock decided not to press charges against Smith.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] On April 8, 2022, the Academy made an announcement via a letter sent by president David Rubin and CEO Dawn Hudson informing the public that Will Smith had received a ten-year ban from attending the Oscars as a result of the incident.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Some winners critical of the Academy Awards have boycotted the ceremonies and refused to accept their Oscars.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] The first to do so was screenwriter Dudley Nichols (Best Writing in 1935 for *The Informer*).
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Nichols boycotted the 8th Academy Awards ceremony because of conflicts between the Academy and the Writers' Guild.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Nichols eventually accepted the 1935 award three years later, at the 1938 ceremony.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Nichols was nominated for three further Academy Awards during his career.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Scott became the second person to refuse his award (Best Actor in 1970 for *Patton*) at the 43rd Academy Awards ceremony.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Scott described it as a "meat parade", saying, "I don't want any part of it".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] The third person to refuse the award was Marlon Brando, who refused his award (Best Actor for 1972's *The Godfather*), citing the film industry's discrimination against and mistreatment of Native Americans.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] At the 45th Academy Awards ceremony, Brando asked actress and civil rights activist Sacheen Littlefeather to read a 15-page speech in his place, detailing his criticisms, for which there was booing and cheering by the audience.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] In 2022, Littlefeather was accused by her sisters of misrepresenting her ancestry as Native American.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Adding to the controversy was that the award for Best Animated Short Film (the nominees for which were mostly made up of shorts not aimed at children) was one of the eight categories that were not presented during the live broadcast.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Alberto Mielgo, director of *The Windshield Wiper*, later gave an acceptance speech for the Oscar: "Animation is an art that includes every single art that you can imagine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] I'm very honored because this is just the beginning of what we can do with animation." Some speculations suggested that the speech played a role in the decision not to broadcast the award.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] The PG-13-rated *The Boy and the Heron* would subsequently win the award.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] It has become a tradition to give out gift bags to the presenters and performers at the Oscars.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] In recent years, these gifts have been extended to award nominees and winners.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] The value of each of these gift bags can reach into the tens of thousands of dollars.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] In 2014, the value was reported to be as high as $80,000.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] The value has risen to the point where the U.S.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Internal Revenue Service issued a statement regarding the gifts and their taxable status.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Some of the gifts have even had a "risque" element to them; in 2014, the adult products retailer Adam & Eve had a "Secret Room Gifting Suite".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] Celebrities visiting the gifting suite included Judith Hoag, Carolyn Hennesy, Kate Linder, Chris Mulkey, Jim O'Heir and John Salley.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/academy-award-p02] From 2006 onwards, results are Live+SD; all previous years are live viewing.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/acqua-panna] The Acqua Panna source is located 1,100 m (3,700 feet) high in the Apennine Mountains of Tuscany, to the north of Florence.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/acqua-panna] In the 16th century the powerful ruling family of the Medicis in Florence owned the spring, and it was fenced off as their private property.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/acqua-panna] The family had fresh drinking water from this preserved natural spring, whereas many other unclaimed springs were contaminated with animal waste.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/acqua-panna] The brand belongs to Sanpellegrino S.p.A subsidiary of Nestlé, and is sold in Europe, the Americas and Asia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/acqua-panna] Acqua Panna is bottled in glass (25 cl, 50 cl, 75 cl, 1 L) and plastic (33 cl, 50cl, 75 cl, 1 L) bottles.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé (the biggest food company in the world) has been involved in a significant number of controversies and has been criticized a number of times for its business practices.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Concern about Nestlé's "aggressive marketing" of their breast milk substitutes, particularly in developing countries, first arose in the 1970s.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Critics have accused Nestlé of discouraging mothers from breastfeeding and suggesting that their baby formula is healthier than breastfeeding through marketing campaigns which suggested the formula was used by health professionals.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] This included Nestlé distributing free formula samples in maternity units and dressing salespeople as nurses to sell customers the false claim that the formula would help with infant health outcomes.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] This led to a boycott which was launched in 1977 in the United States and subsequently spread into Europe.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The boycott was suspended in the US in 1984, after Nestlé agreed to follow an international marketing code endorsed by the World Health Organization (WHO), but was relaunched in 1989.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] As of 2011, the company is included in the FTSE4Good Index designed to help enable ethical investment.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] However, the company allegedly repeated these same marketing practices in developing countries like Pakistan in the 1990s.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] A Pakistani salesman named Syed Aamir Raza Hussain became a whistle-blower against his former employer Nestlé.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In 1999, two years after he left Nestlé, Hussain released a report in association with the non-profit organization Baby Milk Action, in which he alleged that Nestlé was encouraging doctors to push its infant formula products over breastfeeding.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] This story inspired the acclaimed 2014 Indian film *Tigers* by the Oscar-winning Bosnian director Danis Tanović.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In May 2011, nineteen Laos-based international NGOs, including Save the Children, Oxfam, CARE International, Plan International, and World Vision launched a boycott of Nestlé with an open letter.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Among other unethical practices, they criticized a failure to translate labeling and health information into local languages and accused the company of giving incentives to doctors and nurses to promote the use of infant formula.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Lefever and the Ethics and Public Policy Center were criticized for accepting a $25,000 contribution from Nestlé while the organization was in the process of developing a report investigating medical care in developing nations which was never published.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] It was alleged that this contribution affected the release of the report and led to the author of the report submitting an article to *Fortune* magazine praising the company's position.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé has been under investigation in China since 2011 over allegations that the company bribed hospital staff to obtain the medical records of patients and push its infant formula to increase sales.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] This was found to be in violation of a 1995 Chinese regulation that aims to secure the impartiality of medical staff by banning hospitals and academic institutions from promoting instant formula to families.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] As a consequence, six Nestlé employees were given prison sentences between one and six years.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Multiple reports have documented the widespread use of child labor in cocoa production, as well as slavery and child trafficking, throughout West African plantations, on which Nestlé and other major chocolate companies rely.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] According to the 2010 documentary, *The Dark Side of Chocolate*, the children working are typically 12 to 15 years old.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The Fair Labor Association has criticized Nestlé for not carrying out proper checks.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The suit alleged that children were trafficked to Ivory Coast, forced into slavery, and experienced frequent beatings on a cocoa plantation.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] District Court for the Central District of California determined corporations cannot be held liable for violations of international law and dismissed the suit.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals reversed the decision.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Supreme Court declined to hear Nestlé's appeal of the Ninth Circuit's decision.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In 2019, Nestlé announced that they could not guarantee that their chocolate products were free from child slave labor, as they could trace only 49% of their purchasing back to the farm level.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The *Washington Post* noted that the commitment taken in 2001 to eradicate such practices within four years had not been kept, neither at the due deadline of 2005, nor within the revised deadlines of 2008 and 2010, and that the result was not likely to be achieved for 2020 either.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In 2021, Nestlé was named in a class action lawsuit filed by eight former child slaves from Mali who alleged that the company aided and abetted their enslavement on cocoa plantations in Ivory Coast.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The lawsuit was dismissed in June 2021 by the Supreme Court of the United States on the grounds that all of the conduct alleged in the lawsuit had "occurred in the Ivory Coast," and American laws, specifically the Alien Tort Statute, could not be applied in a extraterrestrial way.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] At the conclusion of a year-long self-imposed investigation in November 2015, Nestlé disclosed that seafood products sourced in Thailand were produced with forced labor.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé is not a major purchaser of seafood in Southeast Asia, but does some business in Thailand – primarily for its Purina cat food.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The study found virtually all US and European companies buying seafood from Thailand are exposed to the same risks of abuse in their supply chains.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] This type of disclosure was a surprise to many in the industry because international companies rarely acknowledge abuses in supply chains.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé was expected to launch a year-long program in 2016 focused on protecting workers across its supply chain.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The company has promised to impose new requirements on all potential suppliers, train boat owners and captains about human rights, and hire auditors to check for compliance with new rules.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In late September 2008, the Hong Kong government found melamine in a Chinese-made Nestlé milk product.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Six infants died from kidney damage, and a further 860 babies were hospitalized.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The Dairy Farm milk was made by Nestlé's division in the Chinese coastal city Qingdao.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé affirmed that all its products were safe and were not made from milk adulterated with melamine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] On 2 October 2008, the Taiwan Health ministry announced that six types of milk powders produced in China by Nestlé contained low-level traces of melamine, and were "removed from the shelves".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] As of 2013, Nestlé has implemented initiatives to prevent contamination and utilizes what it calls a "factory and farmers" model that eliminates the middleman.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Farmers bring milk directly to a network of Nestlé-owned collection centers, where a computerized system samples, tests, and tags each batch of milk.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] To reduce further the risk of contamination at the source, the company provides farmers with continuous training and assistance in cow selection, feed quality, storage, and other areas.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In 2014, the company opened the Nestlé Food Safety Institute (NFSI) in Beijing that will help meet China's growing demand for healthy and safe food, one of the top three concerns among Chinese consumers.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In an incident in 2015, weevils and fungus were found in Cerelac cereal, recommended for kids.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In January 2026, six babies became ill after consuming Nestlé baby food linked to a safety alert over possible cereulide contamination, which can cause vomiting and diarrhea.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé has also received additional illness reports, though a direct link has not been confirmed.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] French authorities are investigating whether two infant deaths are connected.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The company recalled affected products in early January and has since launched a global recall covering more than 60 countries.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The recall covered over 800 products from more than 10 Nestlé factories, making it the largest recall in the company’s history.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The contamination was reported to link to the Omega-6 (ARA) oil supplied by Cabio Biotech, a Chinese company based in Wuhan.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In June 2009, an outbreak of *E. coli* O157:H7 was linked to Nestlé's refrigerated cookie dough originating in a plant in Danville, Virginia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In the US, it caused sickness in more than 50 people in 30 states, half of whom required hospitalization.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Following the outbreak, Nestlé recalled 30,000 cases of the cookie dough.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The cause was determined to be contaminated flour obtained from a raw material supplier.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] When operations resumed, the flour used was heat-treated to kill bacteria.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In May 2015, food safety regulators from the state of Uttar Pradesh, India, found that samples of Nestlé India's Maggi noodles had up to 17 times more than the permissible safe amount of lead.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Due to this, on 3 June 2015, the New Delhi Government banned the sale of Maggi in New Delhi stores for 15 days.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Some of India's biggest retailers, such as Future Group, Big Bazaar, Easyday, and Nilgiris, had imposed a nationwide ban on Maggi as of 3 June 2015.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] On 4 June 2015, the Gujarat FD banned the sale of the noodles for 30 days after 27 out of 39 samples were detected with objectionable levels of metallic lead, among other things.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] On 5 June 2015, Food Safety and Standards Authority of India (FSSAI) orders banned all nine approved variants of Maggi instant noodles from India, deeming them "unsafe and hazardous" for human consumption, and Nepal indefinitely banned Maggi over concerns about lead levels in the product.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Maggi noodles have been withdrawn in five African nations – Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Rwanda, and South Sudan – by a supermarket chain after a complaint by the Consumer Federation of Kenya, as a reaction to the ban in India.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In India, Maggi products were returned to the shelves in November 2015, accompanied by a Nestlé advertising campaign to win back consumer trust.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé resumed production of Maggi at all five plants in India on 30 November 2015.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In the Philippines, localized versions of Maggi instant noodles were sold until 2011 when the product group was recalled for suspected salmonella contamination.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The product did not return to market, while Nestle continues to sell seasoning products including the popular Maggi Magic Sarap.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In 2022, a pizza factory owned by Buitoni (a subsidiary of Nestlé) was discovered to have been the source of an outbreak of *E. coli*, which resulted in the death of at least 2 people, with 55 cases being confirmed to be related to the factory.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] It was found to have inconceivable sanitary conditions, with photos showing ingredients spilled on the floor and conveyor belts with residue on them.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] At the second World Water Forum in 2000, Nestlé and other corporations persuaded the World Water Council to change its statement so as to reduce access to drinking water from a "right" to a "need".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé continues to take control of aquifers and bottle their water for profit.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Peter Brabeck-Letmathe, chairman of Nestlé, later changed his statement, saying in a 2013 interview, "I am the first one to say water is a human right." In that same interview, he claimed that it was the "primary responsibility of every government" to provide 30 liters of water a day to citizens.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] At the World Water Forum 2005, Nestlé was confronted with a study about its negative impact and use of corporate power in Pakistan.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In the same year, Pakistan's Audit Agency stated that the enterprise made an "unjustified" profit with its bottled water.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The advertising campaign has been called greenwashing.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé defended its ads, saying that they will show they have been truthful in their campaign.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Considerable controversy has surrounded Nestlé's bottled water brand, Arrowhead, sourced from wells alongside a spring in Millard Canyon situated in a Native American Reservation at the base of the San Bernardino Mountains in California.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Additionally, recent evidence suggests that representatives of the Forest Service failed to follow through on a review process for Nestlé's permit to draw water from the San Bernardino wells, which expired in 1988.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In San Bernardino, Nestlé pays the US Forest Service $524 yearly to pump and bottle about 30 million gallons, even during droughts.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The former forest supervisor Gene Zimmerman has explained that the review process was rigorous, and that the Forest Service "didn't have the money or the budget or the staff" to follow through on the review of Nestlé's long-expired permit.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] However, Zimmerman's observations and action have come under scrutiny for a number of reasons.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Firstly, along with the natural resource manager for Nestlé, Larry Lawrence, Zimmerman is a board member for and played a vital role in the founding of the nonprofit Southern California Mountains Foundation, of which Nestlé is the most noteworthy and longtime donor.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Secondly, the Zimmerman Community Partnership Award – an award inspired by Zimmerman's actions and efforts "to create a public/private partnership for resource development and community engagement" – was presented by the foundation to Nestlé's Arrowhead Water division in 2013.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Finally, while Zimmerman retired from his former role in 2005, he currently works as a paid consultant for Nestlé, leading many investigative journalists to question Zimmerman's allegiances prior to his retirement from the Forest Service.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé approached them in 2008 and they had been considering to trade their well water with Oregon's Oxbow Springs water, a publicly owned water source in the Columbia River Gorge National Scenic Area, and to sell the spring water at over 100 million gallons of water per year to Nestlé.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The plan has been criticized by legislators and 80,000 citizens.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The 250,000-square-foot, $50 million Nestlé bottling plant in Cascade Locks with an unemployment rate of 18.8 percent would have 50 employees and would increase property-tax collections by 67 percent.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In May 2016, voters of Hood River County voted 69 percent to 31 percent for the ballot measure to ban large bottling operations in the area, but in Cascade Locks, the one precinct in Hood River County, voters decided against the ballot measure, 58 percent to 42 percent.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] As a result, the Cascade Locks city council voted 5-to-1 to keep up the fight.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Soon after, Governor Kate Brown directed state officials to stop an exchange of water rights that was crucial to the deal, citing fiscal rather than environmental reasons.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé then acknowledged that the exchange "will not be going forward", marking a definite end to the planned bottling operation.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Although a 2005 court settlement gave Nestlé the right to pump 250 gallons per minute (GPM) from a well in unincorporated Osceola Township, Osceola County, Michigan, Nestlé has tried to increase that rate to 400 GPM.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Its bottled water is sold under the Ice Mountain Spring label.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The local planning commission denied the application to build a booster station to increase the capacity of the pipeline that delivers water to a water truck depot some distance from the town.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Local citizens mounted considerable grassroots opposition to the plan, with 55 opponents testifying against the proposal at a meeting attended by almost 500 people in July 2017.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The litigation has been costly to the small town, which receives its only compensation from a $200 annual pumping fee.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Goliath" situation is drawing increasing national attention.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé approaches water purely as a commodity.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In 1994 Helmut Maucher, Nestlé's CEO commented, "Springs are like petroleum.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] You can always build a chocolate factory.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In April 2021, and after many water rights complaints and online petitions against Nestlé, California's Water Resources Control Board told the company that it has to stop unauthorized natural spring water diversions in the San Bernardino Forest.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In 2018, Nestlé pledged to abide by the "Better Chicken Commitment", which involved committing to a range of improved welfare practices for chicken procured for use in Nestlé food products.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] However, a 2025 review from Compassion in World Farming listed that the company was not providing updates on progress towards complying with its 2018 pledge.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In 2024, Nestle reported that 74.4% of its eggs are sourced from cage-free suppliers, slightly down from 76.3% in 2021.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In Canada, the Competition Bureau raided the offices of Nestlé Canada (along with those of Hershey Canada and Mars Canada) in 2007 to investigate the matter of price fixing of chocolates.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] It is alleged that executives with Nestlé (the maker of KitKat, Coffee Crisp, and Big Turk) colluded with competitors in Canada to inflate prices.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé and the other companies were subject to class-action lawsuits for price fixing after the raids were made public in 2007.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé settled for $9 million, without admitting liability, subject to court approval in the new year.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] A massive class-action lawsuit continues in the United States.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In February 2024, the Spanish *Audiencia Nacional* fined Nestlé with 6.86 million euros for forming a cartel with other dairy companies to avoid competition when buying milk from Spanish farmers between 2000 and 2013.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The farmers can now further sue for damages.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In 2002, Nestlé demanded that the nation of Ethiopia repay US$6 million of debt to the company at a time when Ethiopia was suffering a severe famine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé backed down from its demand after more than 8,500 people complained via e-mail to the company about its treatment of the Ethiopian government.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The company agreed to re-invest any money it received from Ethiopia back into the country.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In 2003, Nestlé agreed to accept an offer of US$1.5 million, and donated the money to three active charities in Ethiopia: the Red Cross, Caritas, and UNHCR.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In August 2015, the Ukrainian TV channel Ukrayina refused to hire a worker of the weekly magazine *Krayina*, Alla Zheliznyak, as a host of a cooking show because she speaks Ukrainian.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The demand to only hire a Russian-speaking host was allegedly set by a sponsor of the show – Nesquik, which is a brand of Nestlé S.A.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Activists of the Vidsich civil movement held a rally near the office of the company in Kyiv, accusing Nestlé of discriminating against people who speak Ukrainian and supporting the Russification of Ukraine.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] They also criticized goods sold in Ukraine being manufactured in Russia and threatened a boycott.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, many international, particularly Western companies pulled out of Russia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Unlike most of its Western competitors, Nestlé was slow to announce any disinvestments or scaling back of its operations in Russia, drawing criticism.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé employs 7,000 workers in Russia and stated they intend to protect them.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelensky pleaded for a stop of business activities that help finance the Ukraine invasion.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé suspended shipment of non-essential items but continued to produce essential food items in Russia.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The company said that "our activities in Russia will focus on providing essential food, such as infant food and medical/hospital nutrition".
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] On November 2, 2023, the National Agency on Corruption Prevention (NACP) has included the company in the list of international sponsors of the war.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Nestlé has been involved in extensive union-busting activity in Colombia since it first arrived there.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In September 2017, an investigation conducted by NGO Mighty Earth found that a large amount of the cocoa used in chocolate produced by Nestlé and other major chocolate companies was grown illegally in national parks and other protected areas in Ivory Coast and Ghana.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The countries are the world's two largest cocoa producers.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] The report documents how in several national parks and other protected areas, 90% or more of the land mass has been converted to cocoa.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] Less than four percent of Ivory Coast remains densely forested, and the chocolate companies' laissez-faire approach to sourcing has driven extensive deforestation in Ghana as well.
[src:controversies-of-nestlé/controversies-of-nestlé] In Ivory Coast, deforestation has pushed chimpanzees into just a few small pockets, and reduced the country's elephant population from several hundred thousand to about 200–400.
